metadata.title: VIOLENT ACTS
metadata.definition: Codes in this division apply to injuries that are the result of intentional violent acts by a person. Such injuries may be inflicted by another person or by oneself. The injury from violent acts may be physical or mental/emotional. The injured worker could be directly involved in the violent act, as either a target of violence or harmed due to gross negligence during commission of a crime. They may also be the indirect victim of violence such as a friendly fire strike during a violent shoot out or witnessing a violent act. Injuries resulting from an intent to harm are considered to be acts of violence regardless of the mental capacity or state of the aggressor. Injuries involving the normal worksite tasks and actions of co-workers should be considered accidental unless information to indicate harmful intent is provided.
metadata.includes: Intentional violent acts by a person; inadvertent victims harmed during the commission of a violent crime; injuries to persons intervening in violent situations; injuries to bystanders or witnesses of violent acts;  injuries from falls or contact as  a result of avoiding a violent act by a person; intentional injuries by persons with diminished mental capacity even while being restrained, moved, or cared for by the worker; distress from witnessing a violent act or the aftermath of a violent act
metadata.excludes: Unintentional or intent unknown injuries resulting from direct contact with a person (61); intentional physical contact without malicious intent during police, military, or martial arts training and during sporting events and training (611); hit by a ball thrown by another person without malicious intent (6429); accidental injuries from all types of guns (641); transportation incidents unless the intent was to injure the worker (Division 2); injuries resulting from contact with animals (62); unintentional or intent unknown drug overdoses (551); exposures to infectious agents (55)

metadata.excludes: Injuries from unintentional actions or actions of unknown intent (61)

metadata.title: Violent acts by other person
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries that are the result of violent acts by persons other than the injured worker when it is known that the act was intentional. The injured worker could be the intended target or an inadvertent victim. The worker could be physically injured or experience stress from the intentional violent action of another person.
metadata.includes: Injuries or distress sustained while attempting to restrain a person acting violently or while breaking up a fight; stress from being present during a violent act by a person which could result in physical harm to the worker, even if no injury occurs
metadata.excludes: Accidental or unintentional  contact with another person (61); unintentional injuries resulting from intentional physical contact (e.g. contact sports injuries) (611); intentional, self inflicted injuries (120); distress from witnessing a violent act or the aftermath of a violent act that does not threaten the worker (13); contact with another without resistance, such as from an orderly arrest, detention, or take down (61)

metadata.title: Shooting by other person
metadata.definition: Instances where a person is shot by another person in a violent situation, acting either with intent to harm others or with disregard for human life. Inadvertent shooting(s) in a violent situation when the victim was not the intended target are included here. Weapons may be firearms or air-powered gun shooting bullets or other projectiles.
metadata.includes: Intentional victims of shootings
metadata.excludes: gun intentionally fired in a violent situation when the injured worker was not the intended target

metadata.title: Stabbing, cutting, slashing by other person
metadata.definition: Instances where a person is stabbed, cut, slashed or pierced by another person in a violent situation, acting either with intent to harm others or in gross negligence of human life and safety, regardless of whether the victim was the intended target. Injuries may be inflicted by actual weapons or improvised objects.
metadata.includes: Stabbed, slashed, cut, lacerated, punctured by knife or sharp instrument; cases of use of a sharp instrument as a weapon by another person; stress due to attempted stabbing
metadata.excludes: biting or scratching by person (114)

metadata.title: Bombing, arson by other person
metadata.definition: Bombing or arson of a structure, vehicle or other object by a person with violent or destructive intent. Arson is defined as the criminal act of deliberately setting fire to property for the purpose of inflicting damage or harm or for financial gain.
metadata.includes: assault by arson or incendiary device; unintentional injuries as a result of intentional arson, such as a firefighter injuries from trying to extinguish an arson fire; stress due to being part of bombing or arson even if no physical harm occurred
metadata.excludes: Fire or explosions-- accidental or unknown cause (Division 3)

metadata.title: Threat, harassment by other person
metadata.definition: Verbal or nonverbal communications of intention to inflict physical harm or cause nonphysical pain, injury, damage, or take some other hostile action on a person or that person's loved ones by another person. In order to select this code, there must have been a reasonable fear of violent action or a pattern intimidating behaviors (such as would amount to cause for a restraining order), such as stalking or harassment.
metadata.includes: non-verbal communications of physical harm; online bullying, harassment; threats of rape; deliberate menacing body posture; brandishing or pointing  weapon; robberies without assault; coercion and blackmail; stalking; suggesting that a person kill or harm themselves; violation of restraining order
metadata.excludes: Argument or intimidation without threats of harm (57);  "toxic work environment" (57); unintentional verbal intimidation (57); missed intended shooting target (111); unintentional intimidation (57); (code the violent act over the threat)

metadata.title: TRANSPORTATION INCIDENTS
metadata.definition: Codes in this division apply to injuries resulting from vehicles in normal operation. Select the appropriate code to reflect the vehicle or conveyance that the injured worker was using at the time of the incident. Vehicles are defined as aircraft, rail, water or motorized and non-motorized land vehicles intended for human occupancy and/or use on roadway or railway systems that are shared with other vehicles transporting people. Mobile equipment, such as tractors and mobile machinery that meet these requirements may also be considered vehicles. Normal operation is defined as forward or backwards motion operating under the control of a person or computerized system at the start of the incident. Vehicles that are moving over the ground surface in an uncontrolled fashion (non-normal operation) are coded in Division 6, Contact. Division 2 also includes injuries to pedestrians, defined as persons who are struck by a vehicles in normal operation but who are not themselves the occupant of any type of vehicle, regardless of their activity or location relative to vehicles in transport at the time of the incident. Vehicle occupants may be fully or partially inside the vehicle or in the process of boarding or alighting the vehicle at the time of the incident.
metadata.includes: Aircraft incidents
metadata.excludes: water vehicle incidents

metadata.title: Pedestrian incidents involving motorized land vehicles
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to pedestrians (non-vehicle occupants) and users of personal conveyance who are struck by traveling motorized land vehicles or other mobile equipment. Locations cited in the code title, refer to the location of the pedestrian at the time of the event and not the location of the vehicle. Personal conveyance is defined as any motorized or non-motorized transport or mobility assistance that is not deemed roadway compliant.
metadata.includes: land vehicle striking building or structure; pedestrians struck while in motorized or non-motorized personal mobility device, including wheelchairs and motorized scooters; pedestrians struck by vehicles while using skateboards, rollerblades, or other non-roadway compliant personal conveyance
metadata.excludes: nonpassengers struck by aircraft, watercraft and rail vehicles and non-motorized modes of transport (21-24); vehicle occupants, including persons who fall or are ejected from and struck by vehicle (26, 27);  vehicle occupants injured as a result of the vehicle hitting a pedestrian; persons exiting/entering vehicles or partially inside vehicles and persons riding on vehicle exterior or in exterior cargo areas. Excludes: Pedestrians struck in non-roadway construction area (253); construction of private roads, lanes or parking lots (253); pedestrians struck by vehicles in non-normal operation (Division 6)

metadata.title: Roadway incidents involving motorized land vehicle
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to roadway incidents involving motorized land vehicles that injure vehicle occupants. Roadway incidents may occur on any part of publicly maintained traffic ways intended for motorized land vehicle travel, including travel lanes, shoulders, medians, and adjoining publicly maintained areas designated for vehicles (e.g. runaway truck ramp, weigh station, toll areas). It excludes private and commercial roadways, sidewalks, and parking lots. Incidents occurring partially on a public roadway are considered to be roadway incidents. Vehicle occupants include drivers/operators, passengers and persons exiting or entering vehicles or persons partially inside vehicles. The vehicles involved can be in forward or backward motion and operating under power or not.  If it cannot be determined whether a land vehicle incident occurred in a roadway or nonroadway area, code as a roadway event.

metadata.title: Roadway collision with other vehicle(s)
metadata.definition: Collision of a motorized land vehicle with at least one other motorized land vehicles where 1) the crash occurs  in the public roadway and 2) at least one vehicle is in motion. If a vehicle contacted more than one other vehicle, code in relation to the first vehicle contacted.

metadata.title: Nonroadway incidents involving motorized land vehicles
metadata.definition: Injuries to vehicle occupants resulting from nonroadway incidents involving motorized land vehicles. Nonroadway incidents include any area that is not part of publicly maintained traffic ways intended for motorized land vehicle travel. It includes private and commercial roadways, sidewalks, parking lots, and industrial and agricultural premises. Incidents occurring partially on a public roadway are considered to be roadway incidents. Vehicle occupants include drivers/operators, passengers and persons exiting or entering vehicles or persons partially inside vehicles at the time of the incident. If it cannot be determined whether a land vehicle incident occurred in a roadway or nonroadway area, code as a roadway event.
metadata.includes: Industrial, commercial, residential, and farm premises; parking lots; private access roads, including for mining, logging, fire fighting, and construction; sidewalks
metadata.excludes: incidents in bike lanes or crosswalks that are part of publicly maintained roadway intended to motorized vehicles or crosswalks (26)

Vehicle occupants include drivers/operators, passengers and persons exiting or entering vehicles or persons partially inside vehicles at the time of the incident. metadata.title: Explosions
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to cases in which the injury or illness resulted from an explosion. An explosion is a rapid expansion, outbreak, bursting, or upheaval.  Explosions resulting from fires should also be coded as explosions, regardless of whether the fire occurred first. Codes apply to explosions of all sizes as well as unintentional and intentionally-set explosions.
metadata.includes: Chemical explosions; pressure (mechanical) explosions; nuclear explosions; explosions, such as backdrafts, that occur due to an established fire
metadata.excludes: Intentional bombing (1115); explosions on vehicles in transportation operations (Division 2); collapse due to structural integrity (63); arc explosions, arc blasts (513)

metadata.title: Fires (without explosions)
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to cases in which the injury or illness resulted from exposure to an active fire or as a result of fighting a fire. Generally, if the worker was considered to be at the scene of an active fire, a code from Event 3 would be selected over other event codes, even if the worker experienced a fall, exposure, or contact incident at the scene of a fire.  If an explosion occurred at any point during a fire, code as an explosion.
metadata.includes: forest or wildfires; structural fires with or without collapse; vehicle or machinery fires, except during transport; small scale fires
metadata.excludes: Fires that result from or produce an explosion (31); Incidents occurring as a result of a fire that is no longer active, such as collapse of a damaged building.

metadata.title: Ignition of clothing
metadata.definition: Instances where an object worn on the person of a worker ignites without the occurrence of a larger fire. This may be caused by sparks or exposure to a controlled source of heat or flame.
metadata.includes: ignition of hair; ignition of worn accessories (i.e. backpack, purse); ignition due to flying sparks without other fire; ignition from intentional, controlled flames in normal operation and heat sources i.e. stoves, radiators, furnaces, kilns, etc.; ignition from small scale, intentional fires, e.g. bonfires or campfires;
metadata.excludes: ignition of clothing from non-controlled fire; contact burns and radiant burns without ignition of clothing or person from a controlled heat source (i.e. touching a burner, hot oil splash) (Division 5); Heat-exhaustion or related conditions from ambient radiating heat (i.e. working in boiler room) (Division 5)

metadata.title: Flash fire
metadata.definition: Short-duration fire that spreads rapidly by means of a flame front through a diffuse fuel, such as dust or ignitable vapors, without the production of damaging pressure (as in an explosion). These types of fires self-extinguish from burning all available fuel as opposed to requiring intervention to put out, and are typically less than 3 seconds in duration.
metadata.includes: Fire ball that dissipates; ignition of vapors, gases or liquids without description of an explosion
metadata.excludes: Flashover occurring in structural fire (322 or 323)

metadata.title: FALLS, SLIPS, TRIPS
metadata.definition: Codes in this division apply to falls and jumps to lower levels, falls on the same level, and slips, trips, and stumbles that do not result in a fall. Jumps are coded the same as falls unless self-harm was intended.  The division also includes other nontransport-related falls resulting in drowning or other nonimpact injuries. The order of precedence is reflected in the order of codes. Injuries due to trying to catch oneself to prevent a fall are coded as falls as is impact with a surface or object due to a slip, trip, or loss of balance.
metadata.includes: Falls, jumps, slips, trips, stumbles, falls into water resulting in drowning; falls on or from vehicles not in transport;  slips, trips, or stumbles without falling; falls and jumps that were curtailed by a personal arrest device
metadata.excludes: Falls due to violence (Division 1), falls on vehicles during transport (Division 2), falls or jumps as a result of fires or explosions (Division 3); parachute jumps (215); injury due to stepping to a lower level (such as, off a ladder, out of a vehicle, or off a curb) with no indication of forcible contact from a fall (such as a fracture or a bruise) (73)

metadata.title: Fall to lower level
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group include falls and jumps to a lower level in which the injury was produced by impact between the injured person and a surface or object, where the motion of the person and the force of impact were generated by gravity, and the point of contact with the surface or object was lower than the surface supporting the person at the start of the fall.  Falls from ground level to a lower level, such as into storm drains or sewers, are coded here. Falls resulting from or causing another harmful event, such as chemical exposure,  electric shock or a contact injury where significant injuries result from both the fall and the other event are also included here. Fall height is measure as the difference between the surface from which the decedent fell to the surface on which they landed. Most falls of one or two stories will be coded as falls from 6 through 30 feet; falls of three or more stories will be coded as falls of more than 30 feet. Distances should be rounded to the nearest foot. Falls curtailed by fall arrest systems should be selected only if the equipment curtailed the fall but caused an injury. If a fall arrest system is not mentioned in source documents, or if it failed and the worker struck the ground, code the height of the fall as usual.
metadata.includes: Jumps to lower level, falls from any structure or object, (including ladders, scaffolds, trees, roof tops, etc.); falls into water resulting in drowning; falls to lower level resulting from contact or exposure to a harmful substance when the fall contributes to the injury
metadata.excludes: Stepping to a lower level without indication of forcible contact (Division 7);  falls resulting from violent incidents (Division 1), transportation incidents (Division 2), or fires or explosions (Division 3)

metadata.title: Fall on same level
metadata.definition: Instances in which the injury was produced by impact between the injured person and another surface without elevation, where the motion of the person was generated by gravity following the individual’s loss of equilibrium and, the point of contact with the source of injury was at the same level or above the surface supporting the person at the inception of the fall. Nonfatal falls are coded here if there is no indication that the worker was at an elevation at the inception of the fall. Falls to the ground after being incapacitated by another event (e.g. struck by falling object) should be coded to reflect that precipitating harmful event.
metadata.includes: Fall from chair while sitting; person unable to maintain upright position; falls due to standing on moving surfaces, such as moving walkways or elevators; leg goes through floor or into a hole without falling to lower level
metadata.excludes: Trips and slips without falls (432)

metadata.title: Exposure to electricity
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries that are a result of contact with electricity.  Contact may be made directly from the power source to the person, such as touching a live wire or being struck by an electrical arc. Items that are intentionally electrified, such as electric fences, should be considered direct exposure to electricity (511). Indirect exposure (512) occurs when contacting an unintentionally electrified object. Household objects should be coded in the 220 volts or less  (5111 and 5121), while power lines and some industrial transformers should be coded in the greater than 220 volts  (5112 and 5122). When uncertain as to the voltage, assume household voltage to be 220 or less, and overhead wire voltage to be greater than 220.
metadata.excludes: Concussive injuries from arc blasts (Division 3)

metadata.title: Exposure to light, other radiation— duration unspecified
metadata.definition: This code applies to injuries that are the result of exposure to infrared radiation, visible light, ultraviolet radiation or other radiation. While eye injuries are the most common, injuries to skin and other parts of body are also included. Injuries may be acute, such as laser injuries, or result from prolonged exposure. Cases where light was deemed to have played a role in exacerbating an underlying medical condition or provoking a reaction to medication should still be coded here, unless the reaction was due to non-medical use of drugs (Event 551).

metadata.title: Exposure to stressful environment without other event
metadata.definition: This code applies to events where the worker is affected by stressful events on the job with the exception of being a victim or witness of violent act(s) or threatening actions provoking a reasonable fear of violence. Stress from being involved in another event such as a transportation incident or fire should be coded to that event. Assume events and actions of persons are unintentional unless source documents support clear intent to harm oneself or another person.
metadata.includes: Stress from workplace harassment or hazing without reasonable fear of harm or violence; stressful work environment; reactions to workplace critiques, disciplinary actions, or perceived "unfairness"; fear of losing job
metadata.excludes: Events where the worker was a victim of or witness to an assault or violent act ( Divison1)

metadata.title: Contact with other person, nonviolent or intent unknown
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to incidents that are the result of nonviolent, intentional or incidental physical contact with another person(s). Physical contact that is clearly of violent intent are coded in Violence (11). Those with unknown intent are considered to be unintentional and coded here. Overexertion injuries are coded in Division 7.
metadata.excludes: Intentional violent contact (11); contact with item (except sports equipment) wielded by another person (6621); physical contact due to the motion of a vehicle in transport (Division 2); overexertion injuries while caregiving (711); exposures to infectious agents or contagious diseases, even if the exposure is a result of contact with a person (55)

metadata.title: Struck by rolling powered vehicle or machinery
metadata.definition: Struck by a machine or vehicle moving over the ground surface that does not meet the definition of a transportation incident. That is, the machine is either not performing transportation functions (i.e. moving goods or persons) or is not in normal operation (i.e. moving outside of the control of a person or computer)
metadata.includes: Struck by moving machinery not involved in transport (e.g. robotic vacuum cleaner or inventory checker)
metadata.excludes: struck by runaway vehicle (non-normal operation)

metadata.title: VIOLENT ACTS
metadata.definition: Codes in this division apply to injuries that are the result of intentional violent acts by a person. Such injuries may be inflicted by another person or by oneself. The injury from violent acts may be physical or mental/emotional. The injured worker could be directly involved in the violent act, as either a target of violence or harmed due to gross negligence during commission of a crime. They may also be the indirect victim of violence such as a friendly fire strike during a violent shoot out or witnessing a violent act. Injuries resulting from an intent to harm are considered to be acts of violence regardless of the mental capacity or state of the aggressor. Injuries involving the normal worksite tasks and actions of co-workers should be considered accidental unless information to indicate harmful intent is provided.
metadata.includes: Intentional violent acts by a person; inadvertent victims harmed during the commission of a violent crime; injuries to persons intervening in violent situations; injuries to bystanders or witnesses of violent acts;  injuries from falls or contact as  a result of avoiding a violent act by a person; intentional injuries by persons with diminished mental capacity even while being restrained, moved, or cared for by the worker; distress from witnessing a violent act or the aftermath of a violent act
metadata.excludes: Unintentional or intent unknown injuries resulting from direct contact with a person (61); intentional physical contact without malicious intent during police, military, or martial arts training and during sporting events and training (611); hit by a ball thrown by another person without malicious intent (6429); accidental injuries from all types of guns (641); transportation incidents unless the intent was to injure the worker (Division 2); injuries resulting from contact with animals (62); unintentional or intent unknown drug overdoses (551); exposures to infectious agents (55)

metadata.title: Violent acts— unspecified
metadata.definition: Intentional violent acts when it is unknown whether the injury was self-inflicted or inflicted by another person regardless of whether the injured worker was the intended target or an inadvertent victim.
metadata.includes: Gunshot wound when unknown if inflicted by self or other person
metadata.excludes: Injuries from unintentional actions or actions of unknown intent (61)

metadata.title: Violent acts by other person
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries that are the result of violent acts by persons other than the injured worker when it is known that the act was intentional. The injured worker could be the intended target or an inadvertent victim. The worker could be physically injured or experience stress from the intentional violent action of another person.
metadata.includes: Injuries or distress sustained while attempting to restrain a person acting violently or while breaking up a fight; stress from being present during a violent act by a person which could result in physical harm to the worker, even if no injury occurs
metadata.excludes: Accidental or unintentional  contact with another person (61); unintentional injuries resulting from intentional physical contact (e.g. contact sports injuries) (611); intentional, self inflicted injuries (120); distress from witnessing a violent act or the aftermath of a violent act that does not threaten the worker (13); contact with another without resistance, such as from an orderly arrest, detention, or take down (61)

metadata.title: Violent acts by other person— unspecified
metadata.definition: Intentionally violent acts by a person other than the injured worker when the specific type of action(s) specified in codes 111 to 119 are unknown is unknown.
metadata.includes: Nonspecific violent acts by a person on another described as any of the following:  altercation, attack, or assault; fighting with another person; injury due to violent acts by aggressive, agitated, or combative person; stress from being the victim or intended victim of an unknown  violent act

metadata.title: Shooting by other person
metadata.definition: Instances where a person is shot by another person in a violent situation, acting either with intent to harm others or with disregard for human life. Inadvertent shooting(s) in a violent situation when the victim was not the intended target are included here. Weapons may be firearms or air-powered gun shooting bullets or other projectiles.
metadata.includes: Intentional victims of shootings
metadata.excludes: gun intentionally fired in a violent situation when the injured worker was not the intended target

metadata.title: Stabbing, cutting, slashing by other person
metadata.definition: Instances where a person is stabbed, cut, slashed or pierced by another person in a violent situation, acting either with intent to harm others or in gross negligence of human life and safety, regardless of whether the victim was the intended target. Injuries may be inflicted by actual weapons or improvised objects.
metadata.includes: Stabbed, slashed, cut, lacerated, punctured by knife or sharp instrument; cases of use of a sharp instrument as a weapon by another person; stress due to attempted stabbing
metadata.excludes: biting or scratching by person (114)

metadata.title: Strangulation, asphyxiation by other person
metadata.definition: Choking, strangulation, smothering or any other type of mechanical asphyxiation by another person. Injuries may be inflicted with hands, weapons, or improvised objects.
metadata.includes: strangulation using rope, chain, or other ligature; asphyxiation using covering of mouth and nose with tape, pillow, etc.; intentional drowning; stress from attempted strangulation or asphyxiation even if no physical harm occurred
metadata.excludes: self-strangulation, asphyxiation or hanging (122); asphyxiation due to entrapment in objects or equipment (Division 6); asphyxiation due to exposure to harmful substances or environments (Division 5)

metadata.title: Hitting, kicking, beating by other person
metadata.definition: Violent physical contact with another person using her/his body or a handheld object, except when contact results in strangulation. This includes Injuries may be inflicted by the person's body, weapons, or improvised objects.
metadata.includes: physical assault without mention of weapon; Intentional acts of punching, clubbing, bludgeoning, hitting with weapon, grabbing, grappling, biting, pushing, pinching, squeezing, shoving, butting, scratching, and twisting or bending appendages
metadata.excludes: Strangulation (113); assault, stabbing with sharp objects, knife (112); injuries by animals (62); simulated fighting or horseplay (61); unintentional or intent unknown physical contact with another person such as being struck by a falling person (61); intentionally throwing an object at another person (119)

metadata.title: Hitting, kicking, beating by other person— unspecified
metadata.definition: Violent physical contact with another person using her/his body or a handheld object, when a more specific code from 1441-1449 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Hitting, kicking, beating by other person while providing protective services
metadata.definition: Injury due to direct physical contact with another person while attempting to restrain or arrest suspects or inmates in a law enforcement, corrections, security, or peace-keeping capacity.
metadata.includes: heart attack after physical struggle; prison, corrections work;
metadata.excludes: Overexertion injuries while pursuing (Division 7)

metadata.title: Hitting, kicking, beating by other person while providing medical or custodial care
metadata.definition: Injury due to direct physical contact with another person while restraining a patient, student, or other ward.
metadata.includes: Biting by patient or person in care
metadata.excludes: special needs or foster group home care

metadata.title: Hitting, kicking, beating by other person— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: All other instance of Injury due to direct physical contact except for during arrest or providing care.
metadata.includes: Hitting, kicking, beating injuries due to co-worker violence; robbers and other assailants; at-work domestic violence

metadata.title: Bombing, arson by other person
metadata.definition: Bombing or arson of a structure, vehicle or other object by a person with violent or destructive intent. Arson is defined as the criminal act of deliberately setting fire to property for the purpose of inflicting damage or harm or for financial gain.
metadata.includes: assault by arson or incendiary device; unintentional injuries as a result of intentional arson, such as a firefighter injuries from trying to extinguish an arson fire; stress due to being part of bombing or arson even if no physical harm occurred
metadata.excludes: Fire or explosions-- accidental or unknown cause (Division 3)

metadata.title: Rape, sexual assault by other person
metadata.definition: Physical sexual contact by a person carried out forcibly or under threat of injury and against another person's will.
metadata.includes: Coerced sexual acts with or without physical force
metadata.excludes: unwanted sexual contact

metadata.title: Threat, harassment by other person
metadata.definition: Verbal or nonverbal communications of intention to inflict physical harm or cause nonphysical pain, injury, damage, or take some other hostile action on a person or that person's loved ones by another person. In order to select this code, there must have been a reasonable fear of violent action or a pattern intimidating behaviors (such as would amount to cause for a restraining order), such as stalking or harassment.
metadata.includes: non-verbal communications of physical harm; online bullying, harassment; threats of rape; deliberate menacing body posture; brandishing or pointing  weapon; robberies without assault; coercion and blackmail; stalking; suggesting that a person kill or harm themselves; violation of restraining order
metadata.excludes: Argument or intimidation without threats of harm (57);  "toxic work environment" (57); unintentional verbal intimidation (57); missed intended shooting target (111); unintentional intimidation (57); (code the violent act over the threat)

metadata.title: Multiple violent acts by other person
metadata.definition: Combination of two or more  different violent acts from codes 111 to 117 when it cannot be determined which act produced the more severe injury.
metadata.includes: Shooting and stabbing
metadata.excludes: stabbing and clubbing

metadata.title: Intentional violence by other person— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Violent acts by a person that are known but do not fit descriptions of event codes from 111 to 118.
metadata.includes: Vehicular assault; hit by intentionally thrown object; intentional shooting by stun gun, BB gun, nail gun, or bow and arrow; human use of attack animal; being held against will, kidnapping without other injury;  intentional pepper-spraying; unwanted sexual displays or exposures; injuries from falls or contact as a result of avoiding a violent act by a person; spitting or throwing bodily excrements
metadata.excludes: Accidental or unintentional  contact with another person (61)

metadata.title: Intentional self-harm
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries that are intentional and self-inflicted. Injuries resulting from the normal worksite tasks and actions of the worker are generally considered accidental unless information to the contrary is provided indicating suicide or attempted suicide or other attempt to injure oneself on purpose.
metadata.includes: Suicide
metadata.excludes: Accidental drug overdoses and overdoses where intent is undetermined (55)

metadata.title: Intentional self-harm— unspecified
metadata.definition: Self-inflicted injuries with intent to harm when the specific type of action specified in codes 211 to 129 is unknown.
metadata.includes: hurting self (action unspecified)
metadata.excludes: suicide or attempted suicide (action unspecified)

metadata.title: Intentional self-harm— shooting
metadata.definition: Intentionally shooting self with a bullet or other projectile from a powder-charged gun, such as handgun, shotgun, or rifle.
metadata.includes: Shot self in suicide or suicide attempt
metadata.excludes: Shot self while cleaning or handling gun (641)

metadata.title: Intentional self-harm— hanging, strangulation, asphyxiation
metadata.definition: Choking, strangulation, suffocation, smothering or any other type of asphyxiation by self with intent to harm. Injuries may be inflicted with hands, weapons, or improvised objects.
metadata.includes: Hanging or drowning oneself
metadata.excludes: intentional inhalation of vehicle exhaust

metadata.title: Intentional self-harm— jump from building, structure
metadata.definition: Jumping to a lower level with the intention of harming oneself.
metadata.includes: Jumping from a structure to a lower level
metadata.excludes: Jumping to avoid danger or to get to another location (41)

metadata.title: Intentional self-harm— cutting, stabbing
metadata.definition: Stabbing, cutting, slashing or piercing oneself with the intention of self harm. Injuries may be inflicted by actual weapons or improvised objects.
metadata.includes: Slitting one's wrists or throat
metadata.excludes: self cutting

metadata.title: Intentional self-harm— poisoning, drug overdose
metadata.definition: Administration of drugs or poisonous substances by self with harmful intent. Substances can be ingested or taken intravenously.
metadata.includes: Intentional ingestion of drug or poison to harm oneself
metadata.excludes: intentional inhalation of vehicle exhaust to harm oneself

metadata.title: Intentional self-harm— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Intentional self harming acts that are known but do not fit descriptions of event codes from 121 to 125.
metadata.includes: Intentional self-harm from stun gun, BB gun, nail gun, automobile crash, fire, explosion; intentionally hitting oneself or external objects (punching wall, head-butting wall or mirror); self-immolation
metadata.excludes: Accidental contact with objects or contact with unknown intent (Division 6)

metadata.title: Witnessing a violent act
metadata.definition: Instances where the worker was not a direct victim of violence or under immediate threat of violence, but experienced psychological distress due to witnessing an intentional violent act by another person or the aftermath of such an act.
metadata.includes: Witnessing a suicide, murder, robbery, etc. in progress; encountering the scene of violence after the event; first responder suffers distress from encountering victims of violent act; witnessing a violent act or the aftermath of a violent act that does not threaten or do physical harm to the worker
metadata.excludes: Being "held up" or threatened during commission of a robbery or other crime (117); being kidnapped or held hostage without bodily harm (119); being physically injured as a bystander to a violent act (11); witnessing an injury not due to a violent act such as a vehicle accident (57); stress from being present during a violent act by a person which could result in physical harm to the worker, even if no injury occurs (11)

metadata.title: TRANSPORTATION INCIDENTS
metadata.definition: Codes in this division apply to injuries resulting from vehicles in normal operation. Select the appropriate code to reflect the vehicle or conveyance that the injured worker was using at the time of the incident. Vehicles are defined as aircraft, rail, water or motorized and non-motorized land vehicles intended for human occupancy and/or use on roadway or railway systems that are shared with other vehicles transporting people. Mobile equipment, such as tractors and mobile machinery that meet these requirements may also be considered vehicles. Normal operation is defined as forward or backwards motion operating under the control of a person or computerized system at the start of the incident. Vehicles that are moving over the ground surface in an uncontrolled fashion (non-normal operation) are coded in Division 6, Contact. Division 2 also includes injuries to pedestrians, defined as persons who are struck by a vehicles in normal operation but who are not themselves the occupant of any type of vehicle, regardless of their activity or location relative to vehicles in transport at the time of the incident. Vehicle occupants may be fully or partially inside the vehicle or in the process of boarding or alighting the vehicle at the time of the incident.
metadata.includes: Aircraft incidents
metadata.excludes: water vehicle incidents

metadata.title: Transportation incidents— unspecified
metadata.definition: Transportation incidents in which the type of vehicle is unknown. If the vehicle was known, but the specific type of incident cannot be determined, defer to order of precedence.
metadata.excludes: Plane incident (21); boat accident (22); rail accident (23); non-motor vehicle incident (24), pedestrian incident (25); motorized land vehicle accident (26, 27)

metadata.title: Aircraft incidents
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to incidents involving aircraft which are in use for transport of persons and goods. Incidents may occur while the aircraft is moving on the ground or through the air. Aircraft are defined as sources in Division 8.
metadata.includes: Plane or helicopter accident
metadata.excludes: Incidents involving drones (Division 6)

metadata.title: Aircraft incidents— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incident involving an aircraft, but a more detailed code from groups 211 to 219 cannot be determined
metadata.includes: "Worker injured by aircraft" with no further information

metadata.title: Non-passenger struck by aircraft
metadata.definition: Pedestrians struck by aircraft in flight, taxiing aircraft or propeller.
metadata.includes: Worker on tarmac struck by plane taxiing
metadata.excludes: building occupant injured when plane crashes into building

metadata.title: Aircraft crash during takeoff or landing
metadata.definition: Crashes when the aircraft is in the process of preparing to leave the runway, taking off, or landing. This also includes in-flight ascent and descent.

metadata.title: Aircraft crash during takeoff or landing— unspecified
metadata.definition: Aircraft crashes occurring during takeoff or landing when a more detailed code from 2121 to 2129 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: Crashes while taxiing
metadata.excludes: crashes with ground vehicles

metadata.title: Aircraft crash during takeoff or landing due to mechanical failure
metadata.definition: Aircraft crash during takeoff or landing due to failure of the engine or any other part of the plane
metadata.includes: Fires due to mechanical failure resulting in crashes during takeoff or landing
metadata.excludes: Crashes during takeoff or landing due to any reason except mechanical failure of the aircraft (2122, 2123, 2129)

metadata.title: Aircraft crash during takeoff or landing between air vehicles
metadata.definition: Crashes between air vehicles when at least one vehicle is in the process of takeoff or landing. Aircraft may be on the ground or in the air at the time of impact.
metadata.includes: Collision between aircrafts on the runway
metadata.excludes: Mid air collisions when neither aircraft is taking off or landing (213)

metadata.title: Aircraft crash during takeoff or landing into structure, object, or ground
metadata.definition: Aircraft crashes occurring during takeoff or landing when the aircraft crashes into an object or surface other than another aircraft.
metadata.includes: Crash into ground, mountain, building, trees, power lines, or body of water during takeoff or landing
metadata.excludes: In flight crashes (213)

metadata.title: Aircraft crash during takeoff or landing— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Aircraft crashes in which the event is known but does not fit descriptions of event codes 2120 to 2123.
metadata.includes: Hard landing

metadata.title: In-flight crash, collision
metadata.definition: Aircraft crashes while in flight.
metadata.excludes: Crashes during takeoff or landing, ascent or descent (212); non-passengers struck by aircraft (211)

metadata.title: In-flight crash— unspecified
metadata.definition: Aircraft crashes occurring during flight when a more detailed code from 2131 to 2139 cannot be determined

metadata.title: In-flight crash due to mechanical failure
metadata.definition: In flight aircraft crashes occurring due to mechanical failure of the aircraft.
metadata.excludes: In flight crashes due to any reason except mechanical failure of the aircraft (2132, 2133, 2139);  in flight crash due to mechanical failure during takeoff or landing (2121)

metadata.title: In-flight collision between air vehicles
metadata.definition: Crashes between air vehicles when both vehicles are in flight.
metadata.includes: Plane and helicopter in flight crash
metadata.excludes: Crashes due to mechanical failure (2131); crash during takeoff or landing (212); single aircraft in-flight crash (2131, 2133, 2199)

metadata.title: Low altitude entanglement
metadata.definition: Aircraft crashes and other incidents resulting from the aircraft becoming entangled with trees or power lines at low altitude.
metadata.includes: Aircraft hitting trees
metadata.excludes: helicopter crash resulting from items being carried snagging on a tree

metadata.title: In-flight crash, collision into structure, object, ground— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Aircraft crashes in which the event is known but does not fit descriptions of event codes 2130 to 2133.
metadata.includes: Bird strike; crash into mountain, building, trees

metadata.title: Incidents onboard aircraft in normal operation
metadata.definition: Incidents occurring onboard an aircraft that is moving along the ground or in flight that are not the result of an impending crash.
metadata.includes: Injuries resulting from in-flight turbulence or sudden drop in altitude
metadata.excludes: Any type of collision or crash (212-213); injuries onboard aircraft that is parked, not in transport (code to appropriate division)

metadata.title: Incidents onboard aircraft in normal operation— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents occurring onboard aircraft in normal operation but a more detailed code from 2141 to 2149 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: In-flight injuries of unknown cause

metadata.title: Fires, explosions onboard aircraft in normal operation
metadata.definition: Small scale fires and explosions resulting from machinery or cargo onboard the aircraft that are not the result of a crash or failure of the aircraft itself.
metadata.includes: Cargo fire
metadata.excludes: cooking equipment fire

metadata.title: Fall, contact incident onboard aircraft in normal operation
metadata.definition: Falls, slips, trips, or contact with objects or equipment while onboard aircraft in transport without a crash incident.
metadata.includes: Falls due to turbulence or sudden drop in altitude; any slip, trip or fall on an aircraft in motion; struck by shifting cargo; equipment or machinery incidents in flight; contact due to turbulence

metadata.title: Exposure incident onboard aircraft in normal operation
metadata.definition: Exposure to harmful substances or environments while onboard aircraft in transport without a crash incident.
metadata.includes: Oxygen deprivation from loss of cabin pressure
metadata.excludes: noise exposure while in flight

metadata.title: Overexertion incidents onboard aircraft in normal operation
metadata.definition: Overexertions or bodily motion incidents occurring while onboard aircraft in transport without a crash incident.
metadata.includes: Bodily motion injuries due to turbulence
metadata.excludes: overexertion injury while in flight

metadata.title: Parachuting and nonpowered aircraft incidents
metadata.definition: Incidents resulting from planned use of parachutes or nonpowered aircraft (e.g. hang gliders).
metadata.includes: Failure of parachute to open
metadata.excludes: striking an object or other person while in the air or upon landing

metadata.title: Other aircraft incident— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Incidents involving aircraft that are known but does not fit descriptions of event code groups 210 to 215.
metadata.includes: Unintentional falls from planes

metadata.title: Water vehicle incidents
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries resulting from water vehicle crashes, collisions, incidents occurring to passengers while riding on water vessels or nonpassengers, such as swimmers and divers, who are struck by water vessels. Water vessels must meet definition of normal operation for the event to meet the definition of Transportation. Incidents occurring onboard docked water vessels (wet or dry dock) are not considered transportation cases. Water vehicles are defined as sources in Division 8.
metadata.includes: Submarine incidents
metadata.excludes: incidents occurring to passengers while onboard water vessel underway such as falls and machinery accidents

metadata.title: Water vehicle incidents— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents involving water vehicles when a more detailed code from groups 221 to 229 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: Descriptions of "boating incident" with no further information
metadata.excludes: Incidents on docked water vehicles (may code in any Event division)

metadata.title: Non-passenger struck by water vehicle
metadata.definition: Incidents involving water vehicles injuring persons who were not passengers of the vessel that produced the injury or any other type of vehicle. Includes injuries to swimmers and divers
metadata.includes: all persons who voluntarily alighted from a water vessel
metadata.excludes: and persons working on docks or around water vehicles.

metadata.title: Water vehicle collisions
metadata.definition: Incidents involving a water vehicle striking a solid object or another water vessel.
metadata.includes: Fires resulting from water vessel collisions; capsized or sinking water vehicle as a result of a collision; incidents involving water vessels that are anchored, but not docked
metadata.excludes: Capsized or sinking water vehicle without collision (223); pedestrian struck by water vehicle or propeller (221); "collisions" with waves (223)

metadata.title: Water vehicle collision— unspecified
metadata.definition: Water vehicle collisions when information about the object struck (codes 2221-2229) cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: Descriptions of water vehicle collisions without information about what was struck, i.e. "jet ski collision"

metadata.title: Collision between water vehicles
metadata.definition: Collisions between water vehicles of any size or type.
metadata.includes: Row boat collision with sailboat
metadata.excludes: tugboat collision with barge

metadata.title: Collision between water vehicle and object(s)— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Incidents involving a water vehicle striking a solid object other than another water vessel.
metadata.includes: Water vehicle striking buoy, iceberg, or other floating object; water vehicle striking stationary object(s) such as rocks, bridge structures, piers or pilings
metadata.excludes: Water vehicle striking nonpassenger (221)

metadata.title: Capsized or sinking water vehicle (non collision)
metadata.definition: Water vehicle sinking or capsizing due to any reason except a collision with another vehicle or solid object.
metadata.includes: Sinking vessel due to a structural defect not related to a collision
metadata.excludes: vessel sinking in a storm

metadata.title: Incidents onboard water vehicle in normal operation
metadata.definition: Incidents onboard a water vehicle in water in the absence of a collision or sinking.
metadata.includes: Jumps from water vehicle in distress
metadata.excludes: Jumps from water vehicle with intention of self harm (123)

metadata.title: Incidents onboard water vehicle in normal operation— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents on a water vehicle in water when a more detailed code from 2241 to 2246 cannot be determined.
metadata.excludes: Incident caused by a collision or sinking of a water vehicle (222-223)

metadata.title: Fires, explosions onboard water vehicle in normal operation
metadata.definition: Fires and explosions resulting from machinery or cargo onboard the water vehicle that are not the result of a collision.
metadata.includes: Cargo fire
metadata.excludes: cooking equipment fire

metadata.title: Fall, jump from water vehicle
metadata.definition: Falling or involuntarily jumping overboard from a water vehicle, without being struck by a water vessel
metadata.includes: Fell overboard and struck head
metadata.excludes: Injuries to swimmers or divers who voluntarily jump from a water vessel (221)

metadata.title: Fall, jump from and struck by water vehicle
metadata.definition: Falling or involuntarily jumping overboard from a water vehicle and struck by a water vessel.
metadata.includes: Fall from and struck by same water vehicle or another water vehicle
metadata.excludes: Fall from water vehicle without being struck by water vehicle (2242)

metadata.title: Fall, contact incident onboard water vehicle
metadata.definition: Injuries resulting from falls on same level or to lower level or contact with objects, equipment while onboard water vehicle in water
metadata.includes: Fall on water vessel docked in water
metadata.excludes: Fall from water vessel (2242-2243)

metadata.title: Exposure incident onboard water vehicle in normal operation
metadata.definition: Exposure to harmful substances or environments while onboard a water vehicle in normal operation without a crash incident.
metadata.includes: Oxygen deprivation from loss of cabin pressure
metadata.excludes: noise exposure while in flight

metadata.title: Overexertion incidents onboard water vehicle in normal operation
metadata.definition: Overexertions or bodily motion incidents occurring while onboard a water vehicle in normal operation without a crash incident.
metadata.includes: Bodily motion injuries due to turbulence
metadata.excludes: overexertion injury while in flight

metadata.title: Other water vehicle incident n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Incidents involving water vessel(s) that are known but does not fit descriptions of event code groups 220 to 224.
metadata.includes: Boat running aground
metadata.excludes: becoming stuck in shallow water

metadata.title: Rail vehicle incidents
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries that are the result of rail vehicle incident involving least one rail vehicle in transportation operations
metadata.includes: Full size passenger and freight trains
metadata.excludes: light rail trains

metadata.title: Rail vehicle incident— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents involving at least one rail vehicle when a more detailed code from 231 to 239 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Non-passenger struck by rail vehicle
metadata.definition: Pedestrians struck by rail vehicle, excluding passengers who fall or jump from a rail vehicle.
metadata.includes: Track workers hit by oncoming train
metadata.excludes: Struck by rail vehicle after falling or jumping from a rail vehicle (2343)

metadata.title: Rail vehicle collisions
metadata.definition: Collisions of rail vehicles with other vehicles, objects, or equipment.

metadata.title: Rail vehicle collision— unspecified
metadata.definition: Collisions of rail vehicles when the object(s) collided with in detailed codes 2321 through 2329 cannot be determined
metadata.includes: Train collision
metadata.excludes: Derailment not resulting from a collision (233)

metadata.title: Collision between rail vehicles
metadata.definition: Collisions between rail vehicles, including train engines, attached or unattached rail cars or other rail mounted vehicles or equipment.
metadata.includes: Moving train hits stopped rail car on tracks
metadata.excludes: Train hits car (2322) or deer (2329)

metadata.title: Collision between rail and roadway vehicles
metadata.definition: Collision between rail vehicle and motorized or non-motorized land vehicle(s)
metadata.includes: Collision between train and roadway vehicle stalled on rails
metadata.excludes: derailed train strikes roadway vehicle

metadata.title: Collision between rail vehicle and object(s)— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Injuries resulting from collisions between rail vehicles and objects or animals, except other rail vehicles or roadway vehicles.
metadata.includes: Train strikes tree down on rails
metadata.excludes: train strikes animal on tracks

metadata.title: Non-collision derailment
metadata.definition: Incidents where railway vehicles leave the rails for reasons other than collision with object or other vehicles on the rails. If a rail vehicle collides with object or structure after leaving the rails, it would still be coded here.
metadata.includes: Derailment resulting from a track problem or mechanical problem with the train
metadata.excludes: derailments caused by hard braking to avoid a collision

metadata.title: Incidents onboard rail vehicle in normal operation
metadata.definition: Incidents occurring as a result of normal starts and stops and regular motion of the train

metadata.title: Incident onboard rail vehicle in normal operation— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incident occurring onboard rail vehicles that are not in the process of crashing or derailing when a more detailed code from 2341 to 2349 cannot be determined

metadata.title: Fire, explosion onboard rail vehicles in normal operation
metadata.definition: Small scale fires and explosions resulting from machinery or cargo onboard the rail vehicle that are not the result of a collision or failure of the vehicle itself.
metadata.includes: Trash can fire onboard train
metadata.excludes: Fire as a result of a collision (232) or derailment (233)

metadata.title: Fall, jump from rail vehicle
metadata.definition: Falling or involuntarily jumping from a rail vehicle without a collision, derailment or sudden stop or start.
metadata.includes: Person falls from train in motion
metadata.excludes: Jump or push from rail vehicle to intentionally harm self or other person (Division 1)

metadata.title: Fall, jump from and struck by rail vehicle
metadata.definition: Falling or involuntarily jumping from a rail vehicle and struck by the same or different rail vehicle without a collision, derailment or sudden stop or start.
metadata.includes: Conductor falls from train and is struck by a train
metadata.excludes: Jump or push from rail vehicle to intentionally harm self or other person (Division 1); fall or jump from rail vehicle as a result of collision (232), derailment (233) or sudden stop or start (234);

metadata.title: Fall, contact incident onboard rail vehicle in normal operation
metadata.definition: Falls, slips, trips, or contact with objects or equipment while onboard rail vehicle in transport without a collision, derailment or sudden stop or start.
metadata.includes: Person falls on subway while it is in motion
metadata.excludes: falls as a result of sudden stops and starts

metadata.title: Exposure incident onboard rail vehicle in normal operation
metadata.definition: Exposure to harmful substances or environments while onboard a rail vehicle in normal operation without a crash incident.
metadata.includes: Electrocution onboard rail vehicle
metadata.excludes: noise exposure while in transit

metadata.title: Overexertion incidents onboard rail vehicle in normal operation
metadata.definition: Overexertions or bodily motion incidents occurring while onboard a rail vehicle in normal operation without a crash incident.
metadata.includes: Bodily motion injuries due to vehicle motion
metadata.excludes: overexertion injury while in transport

metadata.title: Incident onboard rail vehicles— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Incidents occurring onboard a rail vehicle that is known but does not fit descriptions of event codes 2341 to 2346.

metadata.title: Other rail vehicle incident— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Incidents involving water vessel(s) that are known but does not fit descriptions of event codes in groups 230 to 234.
metadata.excludes: Collision (232)

metadata.title: Non-motorized transport incidents
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to incidents in which the injured worker was in transport via a ridden animal; animal-powered vehicle; or human powered vehicle such as a pedal cycle or rickshaw. Ski incidents are also captured here. Injuries resulting from other non-pedal personal conveyance including rollerblades, scooters and skateboards that do not involve collision with another transportation vehicle should be coded in the appropriate division according to the details of the incidents.
metadata.excludes: Incidents in which the animal was neither being ridden nor used to pull a vehicle, such as collisions with deer in the roadway (2622); injuries resulting from non-pedal personal conveyance including rollerblades, scooters and skateboards that do not involve collision with another transportation vehicle (code in appropriate Event division)

metadata.title: Non-motorized transport incident— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents involving non-motorized transport when a more detailed code from groups 241 to 249 cannot be determined.
metadata.excludes: Pedestrians struck by motorized vehicles and equipment (25)

metadata.title: Animal transportation incidents
metadata.definition: Codes in this group include injuries resulting from all types of animals being ridden or to pull non-motorized conveyance.
metadata.includes: Injuries while riding animals in entertainment or competitive events, i.e. rodeos, dressage events, circuses (2413); injuries while traveling in animal-drawn conveyance; dog sledding
metadata.excludes: Animals hitched to a plow when the plow is not being ridden (Division 6)

metadata.title: Animal transportation incidents— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents involving animal transport when a more detailed code from 2411 to 2419 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Animal transportation collision in roadway
metadata.definition: Incidents where persons riding animals or animal-drawn transportation collide with or are struck by land vehicles, in roadway areas. Roadway incidents occur on any part of publicly maintained traffic ways intended for motorized land vehicle travel, including roadway, shoulders, medians, surrounding areas etc.
metadata.includes: Mounted police officer struck by car in roadway
metadata.excludes: car rear-ends horse drawn buggy in roadway

metadata.title: Animal transportation collision in nonroadway area
metadata.definition: Incidents where persons riding animals or animal-drawn transportation collide with or are struck by land vehicles, in nonroadway areas. Nonroadway incidents occur on private and commercial roadways, sidewalks, driveways, fields, arenas, and parking lots
metadata.includes: horse drawn wagon collides with haystack in a field
metadata.excludes: Collisions between ridden animals during sporting events

metadata.title: Thrown, fell, or jumped from animal transportation
metadata.definition: Incidents where the rider was thrown, fell or jumped from and animal being ridden or animal drawn vehicle in any location.
metadata.includes: Horse rider is thrown on a public road
metadata.excludes: rider bucked from horse during rodeo

metadata.title: Animal transportation incident— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Incidents involving animal transport that are known but do not fit descriptions of event codes from 2410 to 2413.
metadata.includes: Struck bump, hole or rough terrain without falling from animal transport
metadata.excludes: Passenger jostled in animal-drawn vehicle (2413)

metadata.title: Pedal cycle incidents
metadata.definition: Incidents resulting in injuries to pedal cyclists and pedestrians struck by cyclists.
metadata.includes: Bicycles, electric assist bikes, tricycles, unicycles, rickshaws, etc.
metadata.excludes: Overexertion injuries due to cycling, unless a crash is involved (71)

metadata.title: Pedal cycle incidents— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents resulting injuries to pedal cyclists when a more detailed code from 2421 to 2429 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Pedal cycle collision in roadway
metadata.definition: Incidents where pedal cyclists collide with or are struck by other land vehicles, in roadway areas. Roadway incidents occur on any part of publicly maintained traffic ways intended for motorized land vehicle travel, including roadway, shoulders, medians, surrounding areas etc.
metadata.includes: Cyclist hit by car in bike lane on side of road
metadata.excludes: fall off of bike and struck by car in roadway

metadata.title: Pedal cycle collision in nonroadway area
metadata.definition: Incidents where pedal cyclists collide with or are struck by other land vehicles, in nonroadway areas. Nonroadway incidents occur on private and commercial roadways, sidewalks, driveways, fields, arenas, and parking lots
metadata.includes: Cyclist hit by car on sidewalk; fall from bike and hit by car, nonroadway; bicycle hits another bicycle on the street; pedi cab hits a tree on the sidewalk; pedestrian struck by cyclist
metadata.excludes: Non-collision pedal cycle incidents (2423, 2429)

metadata.title: Fall from pedal cycle
metadata.definition: Falls from pedal powered vehicles in any location except as a result of a collision.
metadata.includes: Bicycle rider falls in street or field
metadata.excludes: Pedal cycle rider falls as a result of collision (2421, 2422); fall from a bike and subsequently hit by motorized vehicle (2421, 2422)

metadata.title: Pedal cycle incident— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedal cycles that are known but do not fit descriptions of event codes from 2421 to 2423.
metadata.includes: Pedal cyclist jarred or vibrated from striking bump, hole, or other rough terrain without falling
metadata.excludes: Bicycle rider falls from striking bump hole or rough terrain (2423)

metadata.title: Ski, snowboard, and sled incidents
metadata.definition: All types of ski incidents including when a worker is using skis as a mode of transportation, providing ski instruction, or for competition. It also includes non-skiers who are struck by other persons using snow conveyance.
metadata.includes: Snowboarding incidents; injuries from hypothermia after ski crash, sledding and toboggan incidents
metadata.excludes: Overexertion injuries due to skiing unless there is a crash involved (71); dog sledding (241); curling; ice-skating (code to type of incident, e.g. falls or contact); horse-drawn sleigh (241)

metadata.title: Ski, snowboard, and sled incidents— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents occurring while skiing when a more detailed code from 2431 to 2439 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Collision on skis, snowboard, sled
metadata.definition: Incidents where the motion of the injured skier produced impact with any person, object, or equipment that is greater than a ground irregularity while skiing or was struck by another skier or vehicle in transport.
metadata.includes: Collision with other skier or non-skier
metadata.excludes: collision with object such as tree

metadata.title: Struck, engulfed by falling object(s) on skis, snowboard, sled
metadata.definition: Incidents where a skier is struck by a moving object other than a person or vehicle in transport while skiing or standing still on skis.
metadata.includes: Overcome by avalanche while skiing
metadata.excludes: struck by falling object (e.g. tree) while skiing

metadata.title: Fall from skis, snowboard, sled
metadata.definition: Incidents where a skier falls to the same or lower level in any location and is not the result of a collision or being struck by a non-transport object.
metadata.includes: Falls on same level
metadata.excludes: falls off of ledge

metadata.title: Ski, snowboard, and sled incidents— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Incidents occurring while skiing that are known but do not fit descriptions of events 2431 through 2433.

metadata.title: Non-motorized transport incidents— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Incidents involving non-motorized transport that do not meet descriptions of codes in groups 240 to 243. Injuries resulting from other non-pedal personal conveyance including rollerblades, scooters and skateboards that do not involve collision with another transportation vehicle should be coded in the appropriate division according to the details of the incidents.

metadata.title: Pedestrian incidents involving motorized land vehicles
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to pedestrians (non-vehicle occupants) and users of personal conveyance who are struck by traveling motorized land vehicles or other mobile equipment. Locations cited in the code title, refer to the location of the pedestrian at the time of the event and not the location of the vehicle. Personal conveyance is defined as any motorized or non-motorized transport or mobility assistance that is not deemed roadway compliant.
metadata.includes: land vehicle striking building or structure; pedestrians struck while in motorized or non-motorized personal mobility device, including wheelchairs and motorized scooters; pedestrians struck by vehicles while using skateboards, rollerblades, or other non-roadway compliant personal conveyance
metadata.excludes: nonpassengers struck by aircraft, watercraft and rail vehicles and non-motorized modes of transport (21-24); vehicle occupants, including persons who fall or are ejected from and struck by vehicle (26, 27);  vehicle occupants injured as a result of the vehicle hitting a pedestrian; persons exiting/entering vehicles or partially inside vehicles and persons riding on vehicle exterior or in exterior cargo areas. (26, 27) ; incidents associated solely with vehicles and mobile equipment that was not in normal operation at the time such as being struck by rising forklifts or falling trailer doors; walking into a parked car (6); pedestrians struck by non-motorized vehicles, (i.e. bikes, skis or animals being ridden) (24)

metadata.title: Pedestrian incidents involving motorized land vehicles— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck by motorized land vehicles when the location in relation to the roadway as specified in codes 251 to 259 is unknown
metadata.excludes: Incidents that injure vehicle occupants (21 - 24

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle— unspecified
Pedestrian struck by vehicle or object propelled by another vehicle— location unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck by an object or other vehicle propelled by a motorized land vehicle when relation to the roadway is unknown.

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by forward-moving vehicle— location unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck by forward moving work vehicles when relation to the roadway is unknown.

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle backing up—location unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck by backward moving motorized land vehicles when relation to the roadway is unknown.

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle, location unspecified— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Pedestrians struck in work zones events that are known but do not fit descriptions of events 2501 to 2503.

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle in road work zone
metadata.definition: Pedestrians struck in the vicinity of public road construction, maintenance, or utility work or within an area marked by signs, barricades, or other devices.
metadata.includes: Injuries during construction or maintenance of highway structures such as guardrails or ditches, surveying activity, pavement marking, painting, cleaning, or mowing grass; directing traffic, flagging or erecting barricades in the work zone
metadata.excludes: Pedestrians struck in non-roadway construction area (253); construction of private roads, lanes or parking lots (253); pedestrians struck by vehicles in non-normal operation (Division 6)

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle in road work zone— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck by motorized land vehicles in work zones when the detailed cause of the injury specified in codes 2511 to 2519 is unknown
metadata.includes: Flagger struck in road construction zone
metadata.excludes: Worker struck at a building construction site (253)

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle or object propelled by another vehicle in road work zone
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck by an object or other vehicle propelled by a motorized land vehicle in a work zone, regardless of whether the vehicle was part of the work detail or a vehicle passing the work zone.
metadata.includes: Struck by a barrel that was propelled by a truck
metadata.excludes: truck strikes a car and pushes it into worker

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by forward-moving vehicle in road work zone
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck by forward moving work vehicles in work zones.
metadata.includes: Worker in road construction lane struck by oncoming vehicle
metadata.excludes: Forward moving vehicle in public roadway (252) or non roadway location (253)

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle backing up in road work zone
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck by backward moving motorized land vehicles in work zones.
metadata.includes: Dump truck backing over road construction crew on shoulder
metadata.excludes: Backward moving vehicle in public roadway (252) or non roadway location (253)

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle in road work zone— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Pedestrians struck in work zones events that are known but do not fit descriptions of events 2511 to 2513.

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle in roadway
metadata.definition: Pedestrians and nonoccupants of vehicles who are struck while moving in and around a public roadway. Roadway incidents include any part of publicly maintained traffic ways intended for motorized land vehicle travel, including lanes, shoulders, medians, surrounding areas etc. It excludes private and commercial roadways, driveways, fields, sidewalks, and parking lots. Incidents occurring partially on a public roadway are considered to be roadway incidents.
metadata.includes: Struck by vehicle events in shoulder, medians, all parts of area designed for motorized land vehicle transportation and publicly maintained; vehicles pulling out onto public road from private drive; pedestrian crossings and bike lanes
metadata.excludes: Pedestrians struck in marked work zones (251)

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle in roadway— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck by motorized land vehicles in the roadway when the detailed cause of the injury specified in codes 2521 to 2529 is unknown
metadata.excludes: Struck by vehicle in a work zone (251)

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle or object propelled by another vehicle in roadway
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck by vehicles or other objects that have been propelled by a motorized land vehicle under normal operation in the public roadway.
metadata.includes: Struck by a trash can that was hit by a truck on the road
metadata.excludes: Struck by an object that falls from a stationary vehicle (643)

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by forward-moving vehicle in roadway
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck by a forward moving motorized land vehicle under normal operation in the public roadway.
metadata.includes: Struck by a bus driving forward in the road
metadata.excludes: struck by turning vehicles in forward motion

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle backing up in roadway
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck by a motorized land vehicle backing up in the public roadway.
metadata.includes: Struck by a car backing up in a crosswalk
metadata.excludes: Struck by rolling non-running vehicle (664)

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle in roadway— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck in roadway areas events that are known but do not fit descriptions of event codes 2520 to 2523.
metadata.excludes: Struck by turning vehicles in roadway (2522)

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle in nonroadway area
metadata.definition: This group includes incidents occurring in all areas defined as "nonroadway": privately maintained industrial, commercial, residential, and farm premises; parking lots; and logging roads. Sidewalks and pedestrian designated areas should also be considered nonroadways unless they are intended to be shared with motorized vehicles, such as crosswalks and bike lanes. Incidents occurring partially on a public roadway are considered to be roadway incidents.
metadata.includes: Struck by vehicle incidents in industrial, commercial, residential, and farm premises; parking lots; private access roads, including for mining, logging, fire fighting, and construction; sidewalks
metadata.excludes: Struck by vehicle incidents in bike lanes that are part of publicly maintained roadway or crosswalks (252)

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle in nonroadway area— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck by motorized land vehicles in nonroadway areas when the detailed cause of the injury specified in codes 2531 to 2539 is unknown
metadata.includes: Struck by a tractor in a field
metadata.excludes: Incidents in road construction zones (251); passengers of vehicles who fall and are struck (2632, 2732)

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle or object propelled by another vehicle in nonroadway area
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck by vehicles or other objects that have been propelled by or falling from a motorized land vehicle under normal operation in a nonroadway area.
metadata.includes: Worker struck by a cart propelled by being hit by a forklift in a warehouse
metadata.excludes: struck by item falling from rack that was bumped by a forklift

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by forward-moving vehicle in nonroadway area
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck by a forward moving motorized land vehicle under normal operation in a nonroadway area.
metadata.includes: Struck on the runway by an airport vehicle driving forward
metadata.excludes: struck by turning vehicle

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle backing up in nonroadway area
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck by a backward moving motorized land vehicle under normal operation in a nonroadway area.
metadata.includes: Struck on the runway by an airport vehicle backing up
metadata.excludes: Struck by non-running rolling vehicle (664)

metadata.title: Pedestrian struck by vehicle in nonroadway area— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Incidents involving pedestrians struck in nonroadway areas that are known but do not fit descriptions of event codes 2531 to 2533.
metadata.excludes: Struck by turning vehicles (2532)

metadata.title: Pedestrian incidents involving motorized land vehicles, n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Incidents involving injuries to pedestrians as a result of traveling motorized land vehicles or other mobile equipment that do not meet descriptions of groups 250-253.
metadata.includes: Injuries due to near miss of pedestrian by a motor vehicle
metadata.excludes: worker jumps out of vehicle's way.

metadata.title: Roadway incidents involving motorized land vehicle
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to roadway incidents involving motorized land vehicles that injure vehicle occupants. Roadway incidents may occur on any part of publicly maintained traffic ways intended for motorized land vehicle travel, including travel lanes, shoulders, medians, and adjoining publicly maintained areas designated for vehicles (e.g. runaway truck ramp, weigh station, toll areas). It excludes private and commercial roadways, sidewalks, and parking lots. Incidents occurring partially on a public roadway are considered to be roadway incidents. Vehicle occupants include drivers/operators, passengers and persons exiting or entering vehicles or persons partially inside vehicles. The vehicles involved can be in forward or backward motion and operating under power or not.
