If it cannot be determined whether a land vehicle incident occurred in a roadway or nonroadway area, code as a roadway event.

metadata.title: Roadway incidents involving motorized land vehicle— unspecified
metadata.definition: Injuries to vehicle occupants resulting from roadway incidents involving motorized land vehicles when a more detailed code from groups 261 to 269 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: Motor vehicle incident, unspecified; 'MVA', unspecified; traffic accident
metadata.excludes: Injuries to non passengers or pedestrians (25)

metadata.title: Roadway collision with other vehicle(s)
metadata.definition: Collision of a motorized land vehicle with at least one other motorized land vehicles where 1) the crash occurs  in the public roadway and 2) at least one vehicle is in motion. Code titles describe the initial position of the vehicles in relation to one another just before the crash occurred. If a vehicle contacted more than one other vehicle, code in relation to the first vehicle contacted.
metadata.includes: Car with occupant rolls into another vehicle
metadata.excludes: Collisions involving rail vehicles (23), collisions involving animals and non-motorized vehicles (24) roadway collisions and side of road collisions with objects other than vehicles (262); pedestrians or non passengers struck by vehicles (25)

metadata.title: Roadway collision with other vehicle(s)— unspecified
metadata.definition: Injuries to vehicle occupants resulting from roadway collisions between motorized land vehicles when details about the initial position of the vehicles in relation to one another specified in codes 2611 to 2619 are unknown.
metadata.includes: Car strikes bus in the roadway
metadata.excludes: Car strikes animal on the side of the road (2622)

metadata.title: Roadway collision with other vehicle(s)—intersecting, turning
metadata.definition: Collision between motorized land vehicles where injured worker's vehicle was moving through an intersection of public roadways or turning on or off a public roadway, regardless of orientation of vehicles to one another. Vehicles may be entering or exiting travel lane(s) from a private drive, side of road, or nonroadway area. The turning vehicle that of the injured worker or another driver.
metadata.includes: Vehicle ran stop sign or red light; entering or exiting travel lane from private drive, parking lot, parallel parking space, shoulder or median; turning vehicles
metadata.excludes: Merging/exiting from a highway entrance/exit ramps (2612)

metadata.title: Roadway collision with other vehicle(s)—moving in same direction
metadata.definition: Collision between motorized land vehicles where both vehicles are moving in the same direction in the roadway. Select this code if source documents make no mention of an intersection or entering/exiting the roadway.
metadata.includes: Front-to-rear collisions and side-by-side (sideswipe) collisions
metadata.excludes: rear end collisions when both vehicles are in motion

metadata.title: Roadway collision with other vehicle(s)—moving in opposite directions, oncoming
metadata.definition: Collision between motorized land vehicles where the  vehicles are moving in opposite directions in the roadway and they collide but not in an intersection.
metadata.includes: Front-to-front or head-on
metadata.excludes: Head-on collision in an intersection (2611)

metadata.title: Roadway collision with other vehicle(s)—moving and standing vehicle
metadata.definition: Collision between motorized land vehicles where moving vehicle strikes a stopped vehicle either in the traffic lane or on the side of the roadway.
metadata.includes: Vehicles stopped in traffic or at a red light or stop sign; disabled vehicles in the roadway; roadway collision between a moving vehicle and one parked on the shoulder, side of road, or median
metadata.excludes: Rear end collision when both vehicles are in motion (2612)

metadata.title: Roadway collision with other vehicle— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Roadway collision with other vehicle incident with  known details that do not fit descriptions of event codes 2611 to 2614.
metadata.includes: Vehicle falls from overpass, colliding with other vehicle(s)

metadata.title: Roadway collision with object other than vehicle
metadata.definition: Collisions of moving motorized land vehicles originating in public roadways with objects other than a motorized land vehicles. Code titles describe the position of the object that the vehicle struck in relation to the roadway. If the vehicle struck more than one object, select the object that was struck first.
metadata.excludes: Crashes where the worker's vehicle struck an object and then another vehicle (261); non-moving vehicle struck by object in roadway (Division 6); "collisions" with curbs, potholes, ditches (263)

metadata.title: Roadway collision with object other than vehicle— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents where the injured worker's vehicle strikes an object, but the position of the object relative to the roadway specified in codes 2621 to 2629 are unknown.
metadata.includes: Vehicle struck a deer
metadata.excludes: Collision of a vehicle with another vehicle (261)

metadata.title: Vehicle struck by falling or flying object(s) in roadway
metadata.definition: Moving vehicles that are struck by falling or collapsing objects in the roadway.
metadata.includes: Vehicle struck by falling tree
metadata.excludes: vehicle caught in landslide

metadata.title: Collision with moving object or animal in roadway
metadata.definition: Moving vehicles that strike or are struck by moving objects or animals in a public roadway.
metadata.includes: Vehicle strikes deer
metadata.excludes: vehicle strikes moving person in roadway

metadata.title: Collision with stationary object in roadway
metadata.definition: Moving vehicles that strike stationary objects in a public roadway.
metadata.includes: Vehicle strikes mattress in roadway
metadata.excludes: Vehicle strikes disabled vehicle in roadway (2614)

metadata.title: Collision with object or animal on side of roadway
metadata.definition: Moving vehicles that strike objects or animals on the side or shoulder of a public roadway, outside of the lanes of travel.
metadata.includes: Vehicle strikes guardrail or barrier on side of road
metadata.excludes: Vehicle striking building when the car started in the roadway

metadata.title: Ran off roadway and struck object— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Moving vehicles that strike objects where the incident originated on a public roadway that are not described in codes 2621 through 2624.
metadata.includes: Vehicle falling from elevated roadway and impacting a lower level, including bodies of water; vehicle falls into sinkhole

metadata.title: Roadway noncollision incident
metadata.definition: Incidents that occur in the public roadway where there is no collision between the worker's vehicle and any other vehicle or object, but the vehicle is disabled or comes to an abrupt stop.
metadata.includes: Striking curbs, potholes, ditches

metadata.title: Roadway noncollision incident— unspecified
metadata.definition: Roadway incidents in which a collision did not occur but further details of the incident specified in codes 2631 to 2639 are unknown.

metadata.title: Roadway noncollision— vehicle overturn
metadata.definition: Incidents that occur in the public roadway where there is no collision, but the worker's vehicle overturns or rolls.
metadata.includes: Overturn due to shifting load
metadata.excludes: Collisions that result in a rollover or jack-knife (261-262)

metadata.title: Roadway noncollision— fall or jump from and struck by moving vehicle
metadata.definition: Falls or jumps from a moving vehicle in roadway resulting in being struck by the same vehicle or another vehicle.
metadata.includes: Fall from and struck by same vehicle
metadata.excludes: fall from and struck by another vehicle

metadata.title: Roadway noncollision— fall or jump from moving vehicle
metadata.definition: Falls or jumps from a moving vehicle in roadway without being struck by another vehicle
metadata.includes: Jumps from vehicles
metadata.excludes: Fall on or from a stationary vehicle (Division 4)

metadata.title: Roadway noncollision— fall on moving vehicle
metadata.definition: Falls, slips, and trips on moving vehicles from one part of the vehicle into cargo vats or bins or into running equipment that is part of or attached to the vehicle.
metadata.includes: Falling into tank or vat on moving truck
metadata.excludes: falling from garbage truck into trash compactor

metadata.title: Roadway noncollision— struck by shifting, dislodged load in transport
metadata.definition: Incidents in roadway areas when the motion of the vehicle causes the cargo it is carrying to shift or dislodge causing injury. This excludes cargo moving or shifting due to a collision.
metadata.includes: Load comes into cab during transport
metadata.excludes: contact with shifting load while riding in cargo area

metadata.title: Roadway noncollision— jack-knifed or ran off road
metadata.definition: Incidents where the vehicle was out of control, jack-knifes or ran off the roadway but did not overturn or collide with any object or vehicle.
metadata.includes: Runaway trucks; vehicle drove into a body of water without impact; incidents where vehicle ran into ditch or embankment without description of collision; trailed object comes around, makes contact with truck; trailed object detaches from pulling vehicle
metadata.excludes: Collisions that result in running off of the road (261-262)

metadata.title: Roadway noncollision incident— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Roadway noncollision incidents with known details that do not fit descriptions of event codes 2630 to 2636.
metadata.includes: Injuries to unrestrained passengers when no crash occurs
metadata.excludes: overexertion from prolonged sitting while driving

metadata.title: Roadway incident involving motorized land vehicle— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Roadway incidents with known details that do not fit other detailed codes in major group 26. Includes incidents that don’t interrupt vehicle travel.
metadata.includes: Passengers of vehicles in normal operation in roadway area
metadata.excludes: injury to vehicle occupant due to hitting speed bump or pothole

metadata.title: Nonroadway incidents involving motorized land vehicles
metadata.definition: Injuries to vehicle occupants resulting from nonroadway incidents involving motorized land vehicles. Nonroadway incidents include any area that is not part of publicly maintained traffic ways intended for motorized land vehicle travel. It includes private and commercial roadways, sidewalks, parking lots, and industrial and agricultural premises. Incidents occurring partially on a public roadway are considered to be roadway incidents. Vehicle occupants include drivers/operators, passengers and persons exiting or entering vehicles or persons partially inside vehicles at the time of the incident. If it cannot be determined whether a land vehicle incident occurred in a roadway or nonroadway area, code as a roadway event.
metadata.includes: Industrial, commercial, residential, and farm premises; parking lots; private access roads, including for mining, logging, fire fighting, and construction; sidewalks
metadata.excludes: incidents in bike lanes or crosswalks that are part of publicly maintained roadway intended to motorized vehicles or crosswalks (26)

metadata.title: Nonroadway incident involving motorized land vehicle— unspecified
metadata.definition: Injuries to vehicle occupants resulting from nonroadway incidents involving motorized land vehicles when further incident details, specified in code groups 271 to 279, are unknown.

metadata.title: Nonroadway collision with other vehicle(s)
metadata.definition: Collisions between two or more motorized land vehicles, not occurring on public roadways. Detailed codes describe the relative position of the vehicles to each other just before the incident occurred.
metadata.excludes: collisions involving rail vehicles (23), collisions involving animal transportation and non-motorized vehicles (24) nonroadway collisions with objects other than vehicles (272); roadway collisions (26)

metadata.title: Nonroadway collision with other vehicle(s)— unspecified
metadata.definition: Nonroadway collisions between two or more motorized land vehicles where the vehicles relative position to one another, specified in codes 2711 to 2719, was unknown.
metadata.includes: Crash of a tractor and truck at a construction site
metadata.excludes: Tractor crash with tree at a construction site (2729)

metadata.title: Nonroadway collision with other vehicle(s)—intersecting, turning
metadata.definition: Collision between motorized land vehicles where injured worker's vehicle was moving through an intersection of private roadways or entering/exiting a private roadway, regardless of orientation of vehicles to one another. Also includes turning vehicles in nonroadway areas. The entering/exiting vehicle that of the injured worker or another driver.
metadata.includes: Entering or exiting private roadways
metadata.excludes: parking lot intersections

metadata.title: Nonroadway collision with other vehicle(s)—moving in same direction
metadata.definition: Collision between motorized land vehicles where both vehicles are moving in the same direction in the nonroadway area.
metadata.includes: Side by side crash of two vehicles driving the same way in a field
metadata.excludes: Front-to-rear collisions and side-by-side (sideswipe) collisions

metadata.title: Nonroadway collision with other vehicle(s)—moving in opposite directions, oncoming
metadata.definition: Collision between motorized land vehicles where the vehicles are moving in opposite directions in a nonroadway area and they collide.

metadata.title: Nonroadway collision with other vehicle(s)—moving and standing vehicle
metadata.definition: Collision between motorized land vehicles where one vehicle is moving in a nonroadway area and strikes a stationary vehicle.

metadata.title: Nonroadway collision with other vehicle(s)— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Nonroadway collision incident with known details that but do not fit descriptions of event codes 2710 to 2714.
metadata.includes: Collision between turning vehicles

metadata.title: Nonroadway collision with object other than vehicle
metadata.definition: Nonroadway collisions with objects other than vehicles and mobile equipment.
metadata.includes: Berms, embankments
metadata.excludes: Collision with curbs, ditches, potholes (273)

metadata.title: Nonroadway collision with object or animal in path of travel— unspecified
metadata.definition: Nonroadway collisions with objects other than motorized land vehicles and mobile equipment when information about how the objects came into contact with the vehicle, specified in codes 2721 to 2729, is unknown.
metadata.excludes: Nonroadway collisions with other vehicles (271)

metadata.title: Vehicle struck by falling or flying object(s), nonroadway
metadata.definition: Moving vehicles or mobile equipment that are struck by falling or collapsing objects in nonroadway or private roadway areas.
metadata.includes: Vehicle struck by falling tree
metadata.excludes: vehicle caught in landslide

metadata.title: Collision with moving object or animal, nonroadway
metadata.definition: Moving vehicles or mobile equipment that strike or are struck by moving objects or animals while driving, operating in nonroadway areas.
metadata.includes: Vehicle strikes deer
metadata.excludes: vehicle strikes moving person in nonroadway

metadata.title: Collision with stationary object, nonroadway
metadata.definition: Moving vehicles or mobile equipment that strike stationary objects while driving, operating in nonroadway areas.
metadata.includes: Vehicle strikes tree in field
metadata.excludes: Vehicle strikes disabled vehicle in roadway (2614)

metadata.title: Nonroadway collision with object or animal — n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Moving vehicles that strike objects where the incident occurred on a private roadway or nonroadway area that are not described in codes 2721 through 2723.
metadata.includes: Vehicle struck a shed at construction site
metadata.excludes: Vehicle struck by falling tree (2721)

metadata.title: Nonroadway noncollision incident
metadata.definition: Incidents where injured worker's vehicle does not collide with any other vehicle or object.
metadata.includes: Collision with curbs, ditches, potholes

metadata.title: Nonroadway noncollision incident— unspecified
metadata.definition: Nonroadway incidents in which a collision did not occur but further details of the incident, specified in codes 2731 to 2739, are unknown.
metadata.excludes: Falls occurring on moving vehicles in roadway (2634)

metadata.title: Nonroadway noncollision— vehicle overturn
metadata.definition: Incidents that occur in a nonroadway area where there is no collision, but the worker's vehicle overturns or rolls.
metadata.includes: Tractor overturns in a field
metadata.excludes: Jack-knife in a nonroadway area as a result of a collision (271-272)

metadata.title: Nonroadway noncollision— fall or jump from and struck by moving vehicle
metadata.definition: Falls or jumps from a vehicle in non roadway areas not due to a collision or jack knife that result in being struck by that same vehicle or another vehicle. Worker may be partially or totally onboard the vehicle when the fall occurs.
metadata.includes: Fall from and struck by same vehicle
metadata.excludes: fall from and struck by another vehicle

metadata.title: Nonroadway noncollision— fall or jump from moving vehicle
metadata.definition: Falls or jumps from a vehicle in nonroadway areas not due to a collision or jack knife. Worker may be partially or totally onboard the vehicle when the fall occurs.
metadata.includes: Fall while attempting to board a rolling vehicle
metadata.excludes: falls or jumps from a vehicle not due to a collision or jack knife

metadata.title: Nonroadway noncollision— fall on moving vehicle
metadata.definition: Falls on moving vehicles in nonroadway areas, not due to a collision or jack knife, from one part of the vehicle into cargo vats or bins or into running equipment that is part of or attached to the vehicle.
metadata.includes: Falling into tank or vat on moving truck
metadata.excludes: fall on moving farm equipment into running machinery

metadata.title: Nonroadway noncollision— Struck by shifting, dislodged load in transport
metadata.definition: Incidents in nonroadway areas when the motion of the vehicle causes the cargo it is carrying to shift or dislodge causing injury. This excludes cargo moving or shifting due to a collision
metadata.includes: Vehicle cab struck while pulling out stump
metadata.excludes: cargo coming through back window of a truck cab

metadata.title: Nonroadway noncollision— jack-knifed or ran off driving surface
metadata.definition: Incidents that occur in a nonroadway area where the vehicle was out of control, jack-knifes or ran off the driving surface but did not overturn or collide with any object or vehicle.
metadata.includes: Tractor drives or rolls into a lake from a field
metadata.excludes: ran off driving surface and jack knifed

metadata.title: Nonroadway noncollision incident— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Nonroadway noncollision incidents with known details that do not fit descriptions of event codes 2730 to 2736.
metadata.includes: Jarring or vibration onboard vehicle without other incident

metadata.title: Nonroadway incident involving motorized land vehicle— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Nonroadway incidents with known details that do not fit descriptions of event codes 2710 to 2739.
metadata.includes: Injured passengers of vehicles in non-normal operation in nonroadway area

metadata.title: Transportation incidents— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Transportation incidents with known details that do not fit descriptions of any event codes in codes 20 through 279.

metadata.title: EXPLOSIONS AND FIRES
metadata.definition: Codes in this division include any type of injury or illness resulting from explosions or active fires.
metadata.excludes: Bombing, arson (1115); fires resulting from transportation incidents (Division 2); contact with a controlled heat source or hot objects or substances (533), unless the person's clothes catch fire (326).  Injuries resulting from unsafe conditions (i.e. building collapse) after the fire has been extinguished should be coded in the appropriate non-fire event; smoke inhalation where no fire or explosion was present (553)

metadata.title: Explosions and fires— unspecified
metadata.definition: Events involving combustion of materials where it cannot be determined whether there was an explosion component.

metadata.title: Explosions
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to cases in which the injury or illness resulted from an explosion. An explosion is a rapid expansion, outbreak, bursting, or upheaval.  Explosions resulting from fires should also be coded as explosions, regardless of whether the fire occurred first. Codes apply to explosions of all sizes as well as unintentional and intentionally-set explosions.
metadata.includes: Chemical explosions; pressure (mechanical) explosions; nuclear explosions; explosions, such as backdrafts, that occur due to an established fire
metadata.excludes: Intentional bombing (1115); explosions on vehicles in transportation operations (Division 2); collapse due to structural integrity (63); arc explosions, arc blasts (513)

metadata.title: Explosion— unspecified
metadata.definition: Explosions where a more specific code from 311 to 314 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Intentionally set explosion
metadata.definition: Events resulting from the intentional detonation of explosives, except as a violent act with intent to harm. Includes explosives that detonate on purpose or by accident
metadata.includes: Demolition or blasting explosion
metadata.excludes: exploding fireworks

metadata.title: Dust explosion
metadata.definition: Rapid combustion of fine particles suspended in the air within an enclosed location.
metadata.includes: coal dust explosion
metadata.excludes: aluminum dust explosion

metadata.title: Explosion of pressure vessel, piping, or tire
metadata.definition: Rapid combustion or release of pressure of vapors, gases or liquids within a pressurized container.
metadata.includes: Explosions of aerosol cans, automobile tires, steam vessels, pipes, hoses, valves, pump explosion
metadata.excludes: Struck by discharged or flying object or substance (642)

metadata.title: Explosion of nonpressurized vapors, gases, or liquids
metadata.definition: Rapid combustion of vapors, gases or liquids within a nonpressurized container or in the atmosphere.
metadata.includes: Explosions of nonpressurized containers
metadata.excludes: escaped vapors

metadata.title: Explosion— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Explosions with known details that do not fit descriptions of event codes 310 to 314.
metadata.includes: Explosions due to mechanical malfunction
metadata.excludes: exploding batteries

metadata.title: Fires (without explosions)
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to cases in which the injury or illness resulted from exposure to an active fire or as a result of fighting a fire. Generally, if the worker was considered to be at the scene of an active fire, a code from Event 3 would be selected over other event codes, even if the worker experienced a fall, exposure, or contact incident at the scene of a fire.  If an explosion occurred at any point during a fire, code as an explosion.
metadata.includes: forest or wildfires; structural fires with or without collapse; vehicle or machinery fires, except during transport; small scale fires
metadata.excludes: Fires that result from or produce an explosion (31); Incidents occurring as a result of a fire that is no longer active, such as collapse of a damaged building.

metadata.title: Fire— unspecified
metadata.definition: Fires without explosions when the type or extent of the fire is unknown specified in codes 321 to 329 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Forest fire or wildfire
metadata.definition: Large scale fires that spread over woodland or brush. They may burn over long durations of several days to several weeks. Forest fires or wildfires causing a structure or other object to catch fire are coded here.
metadata.includes: Structural and building fires caused by wildfires
metadata.excludes: grass fires

metadata.title: Structural fire with collapse
metadata.definition: Fires without an explosion that result in a collapsing building, structure, or structural element during fire. Small scale fires that spread to become a structural fire are coded here.
metadata.includes: Fires resulting in partial or full roof collapse
metadata.excludes: fires resulting in building destruction

metadata.title: Structural fire without collapse
metadata.definition: Fires without an explosion involving parts of building, structure, or structural element without collapse of structure. Select this code when the fire was known to be structural, but details about collapse are unknown.
metadata.includes: Vehicular (non-transport) or machinery fires and small scale fires that spread to surrounding structures, but do not involve structural collapse.
metadata.excludes: Forest and wildfires that spread to structures (321)

metadata.title: Vehicle or machinery fire
metadata.definition: Fires without an explosion occurring to machinery (whether running or turned off) and vehicles not engaged in transportation operations. If a transportation incident precedes the fire, select event from Division 2.
metadata.includes: Fire-related injuries to non-passengers responding to vehicle or machinery fire
metadata.excludes: fires during machine maintenance

metadata.title: Fire— small-scale, limited
metadata.definition: Steadily burning fires either indoors or outdoors which are contained to a limited area and do not spread to the surrounding environment or structures. May occur in a designated area for burning such as a fireplace or a firepit, or an unintentional fire which does not ignite other nearby materials.
metadata.includes: Brush or vegetation fires that do not spread to surrounding areas
metadata.excludes: trash can fires

metadata.title: Ignition of clothing
metadata.definition: Instances where an object worn on the person of a worker ignites without the occurrence of a larger fire. This may be caused by sparks or exposure to a controlled source of heat or flame.
metadata.includes: ignition of hair; ignition of worn accessories (i.e. backpack, purse); ignition due to flying sparks without other fire; ignition from intentional, controlled flames in normal operation and heat sources i.e. stoves, radiators, furnaces, kilns, etc.; ignition from small scale, intentional fires, e.g. bonfires or campfires;
metadata.excludes: ignition of clothing from non-controlled fire; contact burns and radiant burns without ignition of clothing or person from a controlled heat source (i.e. touching a burner, hot oil splash) (Division 5); Heat-exhaustion or related conditions from ambient radiating heat (i.e. working in boiler room) (Division 5)

metadata.title: Flash fire
metadata.definition: Short-duration fire that spreads rapidly by means of a flame front through a diffuse fuel, such as dust or ignitable vapors, without the production of damaging pressure (as in an explosion). These types of fires self-extinguish from burning all available fuel as opposed to requiring intervention to put out, and are typically less than 3 seconds in duration.
metadata.includes: Fire ball that dissipates; ignition of vapors, gases or liquids without description of an explosion
metadata.excludes: Flashover occurring in structural fire (322 or 323)

metadata.title: Nonstructural fire— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Fires without explosions with known details that do not fit descriptions of event codes 320-327.

metadata.title: FALLS, SLIPS, TRIPS
metadata.definition: Codes in this division apply to falls and jumps to lower levels, falls on the same level, and slips, trips, and stumbles that do not result in a fall. Jumps are coded the same as falls unless self-harm was intended.  The division also includes other nontransport-related falls resulting in drowning or other nonimpact injuries. The order of precedence is reflected in the order of codes. Injuries due to trying to catch oneself to prevent a fall are coded as falls as is impact with a surface or object due to a slip, trip, or loss of balance.
metadata.includes: Falls, jumps, slips, trips, stumbles, falls into water resulting in drowning; falls on or from vehicles not in transport;  slips, trips, or stumbles without falling; falls and jumps that were curtailed by a personal arrest device
metadata.excludes: Falls due to violence (Division 1), falls on vehicles during transport (Division 2), falls or jumps as a result of fires or explosions (Division 3); parachute jumps (215); injury due to stepping to a lower level (such as, off a ladder, out of a vehicle, or off a curb) with no indication of forcible contact from a fall (such as a fracture or a bruise) (73)

metadata.title: Fall, slip, trip— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents where a worker was known to have slipped, tripped, or fallen, but it cannot be determined which of these events occurred.

metadata.title: Fall to lower level
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group include falls and jumps to a lower level in which the injury was produced by impact between the injured person and a surface or object, where the motion of the person and the force of impact were generated by gravity, and the point of contact with the surface or object was lower than the surface supporting the person at the start of the fall.  Falls from ground level to a lower level, such as into storm drains or sewers, are coded here. Falls resulting from or causing another harmful event, such as chemical exposure,  electric shock or a contact injury where significant injuries result from both the fall and the other event are also included here. Fall height is measure as the difference between the surface from which the decedent fell to the surface on which they landed. Most falls of one or two stories will be coded as falls from 6 through 30 feet; falls of three or more stories will be coded as falls of more than 30 feet. Distances should be rounded to the nearest foot. Falls curtailed by fall arrest systems should be selected only if the equipment curtailed the fall but caused an injury. If a fall arrest system is not mentioned in source documents, or if it failed and the worker struck the ground, code the height of the fall as usual.
metadata.includes: Jumps to lower level, falls from any structure or object, (including ladders, scaffolds, trees, roof tops, etc.); falls into water resulting in drowning; falls to lower level resulting from contact or exposure to a harmful substance when the fall contributes to the injury
metadata.excludes: Stepping to a lower level without indication of forcible contact (Division 7);  falls resulting from violent incidents (Division 1), transportation incidents (Division 2), or fires or explosions (Division 3)

metadata.title: Fall to lower level— unspecified
metadata.definition: Fall or jump to a lower level where the fall is known to have produced an injury, but type of fall detailed in codes 411-419 cannot be determined.
metadata.excludes: Falls on the same level (43)

metadata.title: Fall to lower level from collapsing structure or equipment
metadata.definition: Falls to a lower level due to a collapse of structures or machinery, such as manlifts or cranes.
metadata.includes: Fall from ladder tipping over or collapsing
metadata.excludes: fall from tipping or collapsing boom truck or manlift

metadata.title: Fall to lower level from collapsing structure or equipment— unspecified
metadata.definition: Falls to a lower level due to a collapse of structures or machinery, such as manlifts or cranes when the distance of the fall is unknown.

metadata.title: Fall to lower level from collapsing structure or equipment— less than 6 feet
metadata.definition: Falls to a lower level due to a collapse of structures or machinery, such as manlifts or cranes when the distance is less than 6 feet.
metadata.includes: Fall from a chair, step stool or table collapsing

metadata.title: Fall to lower level from collapsing structure or equipment— 6 to 30 feet
metadata.definition: Falls to a lower level due to a collapse of structures or machinery, such as manlifts or cranes when the distance of the fall is 6 through 30 feet.
metadata.includes: Falls described as one or two stories without providing a numerical distance

metadata.title: Fall to lower level from collapsing structure or equipment— more than 30 feet
metadata.definition: Falls to a lower level due to a collapse of structures or machinery, such as manlifts or cranes when the distance of the fall over 30 feet.
metadata.includes: Falls described as three or more stories without a different height specified without providing a numerical distance

metadata.title: Fall to lower level resulting from exposure or contact
metadata.definition: Falls to lower level that were initiated by contact between the worker and another object.
metadata.includes: Struck by hand tool resulting in loss of balance and fall from ladder
metadata.excludes: worker bumped by 2x4 lumber and falls off roof

metadata.title: Fall to lower level resulting from exposure or contact— unspecified
metadata.definition: Falls to lower level that were initiated by contact between the worker and another object and the distance of the fall is unknown.
metadata.excludes: Transportation incidents that result in a fall (Division 2)

metadata.title: Fall to lower level resulting from exposure or contact— less than 6 feet
metadata.definition: Falls to lower level that were initiated by contact between the worker and another object where the distance of the fall is less than 6 ft.
metadata.excludes: Transportation incidents that result in a fall (Division 2)

metadata.title: Fall to lower level resulting from exposure or contact— 6 to 30 feet
metadata.definition: Falls to lower level that were initiated by contact between the worker and another object where the distance of the fall is 6 through 30 ft.
metadata.includes: Falls described as one or two stories without a different height specified
metadata.excludes: Transportation incidents that result in a fall (Division 2)

metadata.title: Fall to lower level resulting from exposure or contact— more than 30 feet
metadata.definition: Falls to lower level that were initiated by contact between the worker and another object where the distance of the fall is greater than 30 ft.
metadata.includes: Falls described as three or more stories without a different height specified
metadata.excludes: Transportation incidents that result in a fall (Division 2)

metadata.title: Fall to lower level resulting in exposure or contact
metadata.definition: Falls to lower level where the worker fell onto or into an object or substance that produces injuries beyond those that resulted from the fall.  This code is typically reserved for cases when a minor fall results in contact or exposure with objects or substances that were independently harmful and excludes falls onto objects or structures where the force of the fall was the primary cause of injury.
metadata.includes: Fall onto running machinery, fall into harmful substance such as a hot liquid or caustic chemical
metadata.excludes: Fall into water (414)

metadata.title: Fall to lower level resulting in exposure or contact— unspecified
metadata.definition: Falls to lower level where the worker fell onto or into an object or substance that contributes to the injuries beyond the injuries resulting from the fall and the distance of the fall is unknown.

metadata.title: Fall to lower level resulting in exposure or contact— less than 6 feet
metadata.definition: Falls to lower level where the worker fell onto or into an object or substance that contributes to the injuries beyond the injuries resulting from the fall and the distance of the fall is less than 6 ft.

metadata.title: Fall to lower level resulting in exposure or contact— 6 to 30 feet
metadata.definition: Falls to lower level where the worker fell onto or into an object or substance that contributes to the injuries beyond the injuries resulting from the fall and the distance of the fall is 6 through 30 ft.
metadata.includes: Falls described as one or two stories without a different height specified

metadata.title: Fall to lower level resulting in exposure or contact— more than 30 feet
metadata.definition: Falls to lower level where the worker fell onto or into an object or substance that contributes to the injuries beyond the injuries resulting from the fall and the distance of the fall is over 30 ft.
metadata.includes: Falls described as three or more stories without a different height specified

metadata.title: Other fall to lower level
metadata.definition: Falls to lower level other than falls resulting from exposure to harmful substance or environment, falls from a collapsing structure or equipment,  falls resulting from contact with object or equipment, or falls resulting in exposure or contact.
metadata.includes: Falls through existing openings (e.g. roof opening or skylights); falls that occur while the worker is standing on an object, such as a chair; falls onto or against structures or structural elements; falls onto or against sharp objects; falls down stairs; falls due to irregular elevator movement, except freefall drop (639)
metadata.excludes: Falls curtailed by fall arrest systems (419)

metadata.title: Other fall to lower level— unspecified
metadata.definition: Falls to lower level other than falls resulting from exposure to harmful substance or environment, falls from a collapsing structure or equipment,  falls resulting from contact with object or equipment, or falls resulting in exposure or contact, when the distance of the fall is unknown.
metadata.excludes: Trips and slips without falls (432)

metadata.title: Other fall to lower level— less than 6 feet
metadata.definition: Falls to lower level of less than 6 feet other than those resulting from exposure to harmful substance or environment, falls from a collapsing structure or equipment, falls resulting from contact with object or equipment, falls resulting in exposure or contact,  or when the full impact of the fall is broken by a personal fall arrest system.
metadata.includes: Fall into pool or body of water from ground level
metadata.excludes: fall out of a truck trailer

metadata.title: Other fall to lower level— 6 to 30 feet
metadata.definition: Falls to lower level of 6 through 30 feet other than those resulting from exposure to harmful substance or environment, falls from a collapsing structure or equipment,  falls resulting from contact with object or equipment, falls resulting in exposure or contact,  or when the full impact of the fall is broken by a personal fall arrest system.
metadata.includes: Falls described as one or two stories without a different height specified

metadata.title: Other fall to lower level— more than 30 feet
metadata.definition: Falls to lower level of greater than 30 feet other than those resulting from exposure to harmful substance or environment, falls from a collapsing structure or equipment, falls resulting from contact with object or equipment, falls resulting in exposure or contact,  or when the full impact of the fall is broken by a personal fall arrest system.
metadata.includes: Falls described as three or more stories without a different height specified

metadata.title: Fall to lower level— caught self or curtailed
metadata.definition: Falls to lower level where, regardless of cause, where the full impact of the fall was prevented by catching oneself or a personal fall arrest system.
metadata.includes: Fall and catch oneself, caught by fall net, caught by personal fall arrest system
metadata.excludes: Fall arrest system worn, but failed to prevent fall (e.g. not tied off properly) (41)

metadata.title: Slip, trip, stumble while stepping between levels
metadata.definition: Slips, trips or stumbles while the injured worker is stepping from one surface to another surface that is either higher or lower. This code is applicable when it is unknown what level the worker landed on or when it is unknown if a fall occurred. If a fall to lower level was known to occur, select appropriate code in Event group 41, Fall to lower level.
metadata.includes: "Missed step"; fall "on" or "up" stairs when fall to lower level is unknown; tripping or falling over curbs, slips and stumbles while boarding or alighting vehicles
metadata.excludes: Falls down steps (to lower level) (41)

metadata.title: Slip, trip, stumble or fall on same level
metadata.definition: Fall on same level and slip, trip without fall

metadata.title: Slip, trip, stumble or fall on same level— fall unspecified
metadata.definition: Select this code when it cannot be determined whether the injured worker fell or not.

metadata.title: Fall on same level
metadata.definition: Instances in which the injury was produced by impact between the injured person and another surface without elevation, where the motion of the person was generated by gravity following the individual’s loss of equilibrium and, the point of contact with the source of injury was at the same level or above the surface supporting the person at the inception of the fall. Nonfatal falls are coded here if there is no indication that the worker was at an elevation at the inception of the fall. Falls to the ground after being incapacitated by another event (e.g. struck by falling object) should be coded to reflect that precipitating harmful event.
metadata.includes: Fall from chair while sitting; person unable to maintain upright position; falls due to standing on moving surfaces, such as moving walkways or elevators; leg goes through floor or into a hole without falling to lower level
metadata.excludes: Trips and slips without falls (432)

metadata.title: Fall on same level— unspecified
metadata.definition: Falls on the same level  when a more specific code from 4311 to 4319 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Fall on same level resulting in exposure or contact
metadata.definition: Falls on the same level where the worker fell onto or against an object or into a substance that contributed to the injuries, whether by impact or additional injuries related to exposure or contact.
metadata.includes: Fall on same level into running machine
metadata.excludes: fall against table

metadata.title: Fall on same level due to slip or trip
metadata.definition: Falls on the same level resulting from slipping on a surface or substance or tripping over an object or surface irregularity. Falls on stairs or curbs on the same level are considered to be tripping over a surface irregularity.
metadata.includes: Fall from stepping in a hole
metadata.excludes: fall from slipping on water

metadata.title: Fall while sitting
metadata.definition: Falls from an object used to sit, when the worker is in a seated position, onto a surface that is on the same level as the object.
metadata.includes: Fall from chair or stool; fall while sitting, fall while attempting to sit, fall while getting up from sitting
metadata.excludes: Fall while standing on chair (41)

metadata.title: Fall on same level and catch oneself
metadata.definition: Injuries resulting from efforts to catch oneself after a fall has been initiated, but do not include completed falls (i.e. hitting the ground) or falling against object or surface.
metadata.includes: Grabbing a railing to prevent fall
metadata.excludes: another person catches falling worker and prevents fall

metadata.title: Fall on same level— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Falls that are not the result of tripping or slipping.
metadata.includes: Loss of balance
metadata.excludes: Fall as a result of slip or trip (4312)

metadata.title: Slip, trip, stumble on same level— without fall
metadata.definition: Slips, trips, missteps or stumbles without a fall or inadvertent contact with an object or surface. Slips, trips, and stumbles resulting in falls are coded in 41 (lower level) or 43 (same level).
metadata.includes: Rolled ankle
metadata.excludes: tripped over oneself or an object without fall

metadata.title: Fall, slip, trip— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Falls, slips or trips where the event is known but does not fit descriptions of event groups 41 to 43.

metadata.title: EXPOSURE TO HARMFUL SUBSTANCES, ENVIRONMENTS
metadata.definition: Codes in this division apply to injuries that are the result of an exposure to a condition or substance in the work environment.
metadata.includes: Exposure to electricity, hot and cold environments or objects, caustic or poisonous substances or oxygen deficiency; drug overdoses
metadata.excludes: Exposures resulting from violence and other injuries by persons (Division 1), transportation incidents (Division 3) , and fires or explosions (Division 3); drug overdoses from intentional self harm (125)

metadata.title: Exposure to harmful substances, environments— unspecified
metadata.definition: Exposures to harmful substances or environments when no information about the type of workplace exposure is known.
metadata.includes: Reactions like allergies, rashes, hives, etc. that stem from exposure in the workplace but cannot be linked back to a specific substance or environment.

metadata.title: Exposure to electricity
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries that are a result of contact with electricity.  Contact may be made directly from the power source to the person, such as touching a live wire or being struck by an electrical arc. Items that are intentionally electrified, such as electric fences, should be considered direct exposure to electricity (511). Indirect exposure (512) occurs when contacting an unintentionally electrified object. Household objects should be coded in the 220 volts or less  (5111 and 5121), while power lines and some industrial transformers should be coded in the greater than 220 volts  (5112 and 5122). When uncertain as to the voltage, assume household voltage to be 220 or less, and overhead wire voltage to be greater than 220.
metadata.excludes: Concussive injuries from arc blasts (Division 3)

metadata.title: Exposure to electricity— unspecified
metadata.definition: Exposure to electricity cases where it cannot be determined whether the exposure was direct or indirect
metadata.includes: Electrocuted; contact with electrified object like machines, power lines, and wiring; shocked

metadata.title: Direct exposure to electricity
metadata.definition: Codes in this group apply to injuries which are the result of direct electrical contact between the power source and the worker.
metadata.includes: Direct contact with power lines, wires and power sources; contact with intentionally electrified objects such as electric fences; power cords of equipment and machinery

metadata.title: Direct exposure to electricity— unspecified
metadata.definition: This code classifies cases resulting in injuries due to direct electrical contact between the power source and the person when the voltage cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: Touched an electric wire without knowing if household or overhead
metadata.excludes: Indirect contact with electricity (512); lightning strike (5112 or 5122); contact with a machine that becomes electrified, not just its electric parts (512)

metadata.title: Direct exposure to electricity— 220 volts or less
metadata.definition: This code classifies cases resulting in injuries due to direct electrical contact between the power source and the person when the voltage is 220 volts or less or described as household.
metadata.includes: Direct contact with interior household electrical wiring or power cords
metadata.excludes: Contact with overhead power lines (5112)

metadata.title: Direct exposure to electricity— greater than 220 volts
metadata.definition: This code classifies cases resulting in electrical injuries due to direct contact between the power source and the person when the voltage is greater than 220 volts
metadata.includes: Direct contact with transformer
metadata.excludes: lightning strike

metadata.title: Indirect exposure to electricity
metadata.definition: Codes in this group apply to injuries that are the result of indirect exposure to electricity. Indirect exposure includes contact with objects which are not intended to be electrified, such as when a conductive material touches a source of electricity.
metadata.includes: Object held by worker contacts a power line
metadata.excludes: powered objects such as a crane touching a power line in a nontransportation capacity

metadata.title: Indirect exposure to electricity— unspecified
metadata.definition: Incidents involving indirect electrical contact between the power source and the person when the voltage cannot be determined
metadata.includes: Contact with a machine that becomes electrified

metadata.title: Indirect exposure to electricity— 220 volts or less
metadata.definition: This code classifies cases resulting in electrical injuries due to indirect contact between the power source and the person when the voltage is 220 volts or less
metadata.includes: Electric shock from sticking a fork into a toaster

metadata.title: Indirect exposure to electricity— greater than 220 volts
metadata.definition: This code classifies cases resulting in injuries due to indirect electrical contact between the power source and the person when the voltage is greater than 220 volts
metadata.includes: Tools or equipment that become energized by contacting a power line
metadata.excludes: contact with object energized by lightning

metadata.title: Exposure to electric arc
metadata.definition: Codes in this group apply to injuries which are the result of exposure to electric arc thermal energy. They typically result in burned charred clothing and skin burn on body, arms, legs and face/head as opposed to internal burns resulting from electric shock.
metadata.includes: Arc flash, arc blast, arc explosion
metadata.excludes: Welders' flash (5221)

metadata.title: Exposure to radiation and noise
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries that are a result of exposure to all types of electromagnetic radiation as well as sound.

metadata.title: Exposure to radiation and noise— unspecified
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries resulting from exposure to electromagnetic radiation waves or sound waves when the type of waves are unknown.
metadata.includes: Exposure to unknown waves
metadata.excludes: Exposure to light (522)

metadata.title: Exposure to particle radiation
metadata.includes: Atomic radiation, nuclear radiation

metadata.title: Exposure to particle radiation— duration unspecified
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries that are the result of exposure to particle radiation where duration is unknown.

metadata.title: Exposure to particle radiation— single episode or single shift
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries that are the result of exposure to particle radiation from a single episode or in a single shift.
metadata.includes: Workers become ill after nuclear power plant radiation leak

metadata.title: Exposure to particle radiation— repeated or prolonged
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries that are the result of repeated exposure to particle radiation over the course of more than one shift of work
metadata.includes: Radiologist experiences health issues after exceeding radiation exposure limits for her job

metadata.title: Exposure to light, other radiation
metadata.definition: Codes in this group apply to injuries that are the result of exposure to other types of radiation, except as described in 521
metadata.includes: Exposure to microwaves and radio waves, radars, x-rays, and other power frequencies; strobing lights
metadata.excludes: Sunstroke and other environmental heat-related incidents (531); explosion injuries from arc flash, arc blast (31)

metadata.title: Exposure to light, other radiation— duration unspecified
metadata.definition: This code applies to injuries that are the result of exposure to infrared radiation, visible light, ultraviolet radiation or other radiation. While eye injuries are the most common, injuries to skin and other parts of body are also included. Injuries may be acute, such as laser injuries, or result from prolonged exposure. Cases where light was deemed to have played a role in exacerbating an underlying medical condition or provoking a reaction to medication should still be coded here, unless the reaction was due to non-medical use of drugs (Event 551).

metadata.title: Exposure to light, other radiation— single episode or single shift
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries that are the result of exposure to light and other types of radiation from a single episode or in a single shift.
metadata.includes: Flash burns from viewing ultraviolet (UV) light;  sunburn and sun poisoning; eye injuries from laser beams or electrical sparks; exposure to laser, infrared light, sunlight, and welding flash, welder's flash; blue light (screen) exposure; strobe lights

metadata.title: Exposure to light, other radiation— repeated or prolonged
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries that are the result of repeated exposure to light and other types of radiation over the course of more than one shift of work

metadata.title: Exposure to noise
metadata.definition: Codes in this  group apply only to injuries that are the result of exposure to noise. Hearing impairments resulting from exposure to a single loud noise (with the exception of explosions) or to prolonged noise are classified here. Use code 5231 if the exposure was prolonged but was limited to a single shift. Use code 5232 for repeated exposures to noise over more than one shift.
metadata.excludes: noise from explosions (31)

metadata.title: Exposure to noise— duration unspecified
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries where the duration of the exposure to noise is unknown.
metadata.includes: Cases where duration of exposure (brief, prolonged, and repeated) cannot be determined

metadata.title: Exposure to noise— single episode or single shift
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries due to a single, brief noise event.
metadata.includes: Sonic boom
metadata.excludes: noise from a gunshot

metadata.title: Exposure to noise— repeated or prolonged
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries due to long term exposure to noise in the workplace for longer than one shift.
metadata.includes: Hearing loss from machinery noise over more than one shift; hearing loss due to working on the airport tarmac, longer than one shift

metadata.title: Exposure to temperature extremes
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries that are the result of exposure to general heat or cold in the environment (531 or 532) or from contact with hot or cold objects or substances (533 or 534).
metadata.includes: Heat exhaustion
metadata.excludes: heat stroke

metadata.title: Exposure to temperature extremes— unspecified
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries resulting from temperature extremes when the exposure cannot be determined to be from heat or cold or from the environment or an object.

metadata.title: Exposure to environmental heat
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries and illnesses resulting from ambient heat and high temperatures in the workplace where direct contact with a heated object did not occur. Cases where heat was deemed to have played a role in exacerbating an underlying medical condition or provoking a reaction to medication should still be coded here, unless the reaction was due to non-medical use of drugs (551).
metadata.includes: Heat exhaustion, heat stroke, hyperthermia, or fatigue from high temperatures in any work environment; working around furnaces, kilns or other heat producing equipment without direct contact with hot objects
metadata.excludes: Injuries from exposure to the sun's rays or other electromagnetic radiations (522)

metadata.title: Exposure to environmental heat— unspecified
Exposure to environmental heat— indoor
metadata.includes: Worker experienced effects of heat after working in boiler room

metadata.title: Exposure to environmental heat— outdoor
metadata.includes: Worker experienced heat stroke after working outside on a hot day

metadata.title: Exposure to environmental cold
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries and illnesses resulting from cold temperatures in the workplace where direct contact with a cold object did not occur.
metadata.includes: Freezing
metadata.excludes: frostbite or hypothermia

metadata.title: Exposure to environmental cold— unspecified
Exposure to environmental cold— indoor
metadata.includes: Worker was accidently locked in freezer

metadata.title: Exposure to environmental cold— outdoor
metadata.includes: Worker experienced hypothermia after working outdoors

metadata.title: Contact with hot objects or substances
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries due to contact with hot objects or substances.
metadata.includes: Contact with heat sources such as stoves, welding torches, or hot fluids; contact with fire and flames from stoves, campfires, torches, cigarettes, furnaces, etc. and radiant heat emitted from such sources; contact with objects that are hot due to environmental heat such as metal object heated by exposure to the sun
metadata.excludes: Unintentional and uncontrolled fires and explosions (Division 3)

metadata.title: Contact with cold objects or substances
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries due to contact with cold objects or substances.
metadata.includes: contact with dry ice, freezer surfaces, liquid nitrogen, etc.; contact with objects that are cold due to environmental cold, such as outside metal signs, light poles, etc.
metadata.excludes: injuries and illnesses from environmental cold (532)

metadata.title: Exposure to air and water pressure change
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries that are the result of bodily reaction to changes in air and water pressure.

metadata.title: Exposure to air and water pressure change— unspecified
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries from bodily reactions to changes in pressure when it is unknown whether air pressure or water pressure was responsible.
metadata.includes: Decompression illness when the medium of pressure cannot be determined

metadata.title: Exposure to change in water pressure
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries from bodily reactions to changes in water pressure.
metadata.includes: Decompression illness, caisson disease, or the bends due to diving

metadata.title: Exposure to change in air pressure
metadata.definition: This code classifies injuries from bodily reactions to changes in air pressure.
metadata.includes: Altitude sickness
metadata.excludes: Being struck by pressurized air being discharged from a hose or compressor (6421)

metadata.title: Exposure to harmful substances
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries that are the result of the inhalation, absorption (skin contact), injection or needle stick, or ingestion of harmful substances.  Medical complications and sequelae, such a cut or laceration from an initial injury that becomes infected due to exposure, should be coded to the event which caused the initial injury.
metadata.includes: Poisoning through inhalation or ingestion; exposure to allergens; contagious and infectious diseases; drug overdoses; exposure to caustic, noxious, allergenic substances, drugs, infectious agents
metadata.excludes: Violence by other person (11)

metadata.title: Exposure to harmful substances— unspecified
metadata.definition: Injuries that are a result of exposure to harmful substances when a more specific code from 551 to 558 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: Exposure via a human or animal vector when the specific route of exposure is unknown

metadata.title: Drug, alcohol overdose
metadata.definition: Overdoses from drugs and alcohol that were not prescribed by a physician or were not used according to prescription, regardless of delivery mechanism when self-harm was unintentional or the intent to harm is unknown.
metadata.includes: Drug overdoses of unknown intention; intentional use of non-drug substances such as inhalants, grain alcohol, detergent pods, etc.
metadata.excludes: Accidental exposures to drugs, such as during manufacture, dispensing, or administration of a drug (552-559), or law enforcement activities; drugs taken in therapeutic use (552-559); vaccines (552, 553, 554); suicides and other purposeful injuries resulting from drugs (Division 1)

metadata.title: Reaction to prescribed medication or vaccines
metadata.definition: Reactions to medicines and vaccines used as prescribed by a medical professional. Medications may be taken via any delivery mechanism (ingestion, injection, etc.)
metadata.includes: Reaction to flu shot
metadata.excludes: Recreational drug use (551)

metadata.title: Inhalation of harmful substance
metadata.definition: Unintentional inhalation of gases or airborne particulates.
metadata.includes: Inhalation of dust and fumes, inhalation of chemicals and smoke
metadata.excludes: Choking on substance(562), drowning (56); intentional inhalation of substance for recreational purposes (551);  intentional inhalation of substance for self-harm purposes (125)

metadata.title: Inhalation of harmful substance— unspecified
metadata.definition: Inhalation of gases or airborne particulates where the length of time of the exposure is unknown.

metadata.title: Inhalation of harmful substance— single episode or single shift
metadata.definition: Inhalation of gases or airborne particulates limited to a single shift.
metadata.includes: Smoke inhalation in the absence of a fire or explosion
metadata.excludes: inhalation of motor exhaust

metadata.title: Inhalation of harmful substance— repeated or prolonged
metadata.definition: Inhalation of gases or airborne particulates that exceed a single shift or occur daily over a prolonged period.
metadata.includes: Temp worker experienced respiratory symptoms after a week of being hire to paint house.
metadata.excludes: Intentional self harm by inhalation of substance (125)

metadata.title: Ingestion of harmful substance
metadata.definition: Ingestion or digestion of a substance producing an adverse reaction.
metadata.includes: Allergic reaction to food ingested
metadata.excludes: accidental ingestion of substances

metadata.title: Exposure to harmful substance through exposed tissue
metadata.definition: Codes in this group apply to exposure to harmful substances through skin, eyes, or other exposed tissue. Types of exposures may include chemicals or other caustic agents, allergens, infectious agents, and blood or body fluids.

metadata.title: Exposure to harmful substance through exposed tissue— unspecified
Unintentional needlestick or sharps injury
metadata.definition: Exposures that are the result of unintentional contact with hypodermic needles and other medical sharps.
metadata.includes: Clean sharps and dirty sharps injuries

metadata.title: Exposure through wound or broken skin
metadata.definition: Exposure to harmful substances where the skin was already broken at the time of exposure. Types of exposures may include chemicals or other caustic agents, allergens, infectious agents, blood or body fluids
metadata.includes: Bodily fluid splash on open wound
metadata.excludes: exposure through already-present dermatitis or eczema

metadata.title: Exposure through intact tissue
metadata.definition: Exposure to harmful substances such as chemicals or other caustic agents, allergens, infectious agents, blood or body fluids where the skin was intact at the point of contact
metadata.includes: Skin contact with chemicals
metadata.excludes: contact with harmful substances through eyes

metadata.title: Multiple types of exposure through exposed tissue
Exposure to harmful substance through exposed tissue— n.e.c.
Exposure to harmful substance—multiple routes of exposure
metadata.definition: Combination of two or more different exposures from groups 552 to 555.
metadata.includes: Exposure through inhalation and ingestion

metadata.title: Exposure to other harmful substances— n.e.c.
Exposure to oxygen deficiency
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries that are the result of lack of oxygen without the involvement of harmful substances and when no other event category applies. Drowning and nonfatal submersions are classified here if no other event applies.
metadata.excludes: Intentional strangulations or asphyxiations (Division 1); drowning and submersions from transportation incidents (Division 2); asphyxiations from fires and explosions (Division 3); drowning and submersions that result from falls (Division 4); asphyxiation due to inhalation of harmful substance, alone or in combination with oxygen deficient environment (553);  oxygen deficient environments and physical restriction of breathing resulting from cave-ins or engulfments (63);  strangulations from being caught in running equipment (65)

metadata.title: Exposure to oxygen deficiency— unspecified
metadata.definition: Injuries due to oxygen deficiency where the cause cannot be determined.
metadata.excludes: Altitude sickness (542)

metadata.title: Drowning, submersion without other event
metadata.includes: Swimmer drowns
metadata.excludes: diver running out of air while underwater

metadata.title: Choking on object or substance
metadata.definition: Injuries where the windpipe is physically blocked by an object or substance injected.
metadata.includes: Worker chokes on food at desk
metadata.excludes: Injuries sustained through abdominal thrusts or Heimlich Maneuver (66)

metadata.title: Oxygen displacement
metadata.definition: Injuries that are a result of oxygen being displaced by another gas.
metadata.includes: Nitrogen leak
metadata.excludes: Oxygen within a space being displaced by harmful gas (5531)

metadata.title: Exposure to oxygen deficiency— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Oxygen deficiency that is known but does not fit descriptions of codes 561 and 563.
metadata.includes: Auto-erotic asphyxiation

metadata.title: Exposure to stressful environment without other event
metadata.definition: This code applies to events where the worker is affected by stressful events on the job with the exception of being a victim or witness of violent act(s) or threatening actions provoking a reasonable fear of violence. Stress from being involved in another event such as a transportation incident or fire should be coded to that event. Assume events and actions of persons are unintentional unless source documents support clear intent to harm oneself or another person.
metadata.includes: Stress from workplace harassment or hazing without reasonable fear of harm or violence; stressful work environment; reactions to workplace critiques, disciplinary actions, or perceived "unfairness"; fear of losing job
metadata.excludes: Events where the worker was a victim of or witness to an assault or violent act ( Divison1)

metadata.title: Exposure to stressful environment without other event— duration unspecified
metadata.definition: Exposure to workplace stress of unknown duration

metadata.title: Exposure to stressful environment— prolonged
metadata.definition: Exposure to a workplace stressor for longer than one shift
metadata.includes: Ongoing harassment or hazing without reasonable fear of harm or violence; "toxic work environment"

metadata.title: Exposure to stressful environment— single episode
metadata.definition: Stress resulting from witnessing a single traumatic, non violent work event where the worker was not the direct victim of the incident.
metadata.includes: Witnessing a car crash
metadata.excludes: witnessing an industrial accident

metadata.title: Exposure to harmful substances or environments— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: This code includes events that are the result of exposure to harmful substances or environments but do not match codes 50 through 572.

metadata.title: CONTACT INCIDENTS
metadata.definition: Codes in this division apply to injuries that are the result of contact between the injured person and the source of injury, except when the contact was due to a fall, transportation incident, fire or explosion, or assault or violent act by a person. This division also excludes contact with harmful substances. The contact can be with a stationary or moving object, equipment, person, or animal.
metadata.includes: Striking against
metadata.excludes: being struck by

metadata.title: Contact incidents— unspecified
metadata.definition: Contact between the injured person and stationary or moving object, equipment, person or animal, when a more specific code from 61 to 69 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: Striking against
metadata.excludes: being struck by

metadata.title: Contact with other person, nonviolent or intent unknown
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to incidents that are the result of nonviolent, intentional or incidental physical contact with another person(s). Physical contact that is clearly of violent intent are coded in Violence (11). Those with unknown intent are considered to be unintentional and coded here. Overexertion injuries are coded in Division 7.
metadata.excludes: Intentional violent contact (11); contact with item (except sports equipment) wielded by another person (6621); physical contact due to the motion of a vehicle in transport (Division 2); overexertion injuries while caregiving (711); exposures to infectious agents or contagious diseases, even if the exposure is a result of contact with a person (55)

metadata.title: Contact with other person, nonviolent or intent unknown—  unspecified
metadata.definition: Injuries resulting from direct physical contact with a person when a more specific code from 611 to 619 cannot be determined

metadata.title: Contact with other person, equipment during sports or physical training
metadata.definition: Accidental or intentional physical contact with the body or sports equipment of another person(s) during sports or fitness competition or training
metadata.includes: Police or martial arts training
metadata.excludes: injuries resulting from physical contact during staged fight

metadata.title: Contact with other person while providing medical or custodial care
metadata.definition: Accidental or incidental physical contact with the body of another person(s) while rescuing or providing care to patients, children, or other charges. Injuries that are solely the result of a care provider overexerting over a patient should be coded in 711.
metadata.includes: Injuries while rescuing; providing care for children or special needs persons; providing medical care, nursing care; unintentionally struck by patient; non-violent contact with social work clients, students
metadata.excludes: Overexertion due to caregiving (711)

metadata.title: Contact with other person, nonviolent or intent unknown— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Accidental or intentional physical contact with another person(s) that does not meet descriptions of codes 661-662.
metadata.includes: Contact injuries as a result of horseplay; accidental contact, such as an coworkers colliding with one another; bumping heads

metadata.title: Contact with animals
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group describe incidents where a worker is harmed as a result of direct contact with an animal, regardless of the animal's intent to harm the person.
metadata.excludes: overexertion while working with animals

metadata.title: Contact with animals— unspecified
metadata.definition: Contact with a non-venomous animal when a more specific event code from 621 to 629 cannot be determined

metadata.title: Bitten or stung by animal
metadata.definition: Injuries resulting from being bitten by a non-venomous animal
metadata.includes: Dog or cat bite
metadata.excludes: non-venomous snake bites

metadata.title: Bitten or stung by animal— unspecified
metadata.definition: Injuries resulting from being bitten or stung by an animal when a more specific code from 6211 to 6213 cannot be determined

metadata.title: Bite or sting— insects, "bugs"
metadata.definition: Bites and stings from all types of "bugs". That is insects, arachnids, and myriapods (e.g. centipedes). Use this code regardless of whether the creature is considered venomous or not and whether or not the bite transmitted an illness, such as Lyme disease, West Nile virus, etc.
metadata.includes: Spider and scorpion bites and stings
metadata.excludes: allergic reactions due to insect bites

metadata.title: Venomous animal bite— except "bugs"
metadata.definition: Venomous animal bite or contact, excluding bites and stings from bugs.
metadata.includes: Venomous snake bites
metadata.excludes: Nonvenomous animal bites (6213)

metadata.title: Non-venomous animal bites— except "bugs"
metadata.definition: Injuries resulting from being bitten by a non- venomous animal
metadata.includes: Dog or cat bite
metadata.excludes: non-venomous snake bites

metadata.title: Struck by animal
Struck by animal— unspecified
metadata.definition: Contact with a non-venomous animal, except bites, when a more specific event code from 6221 to 6229 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: Contact with cow with no other information
metadata.excludes: Bitten by non-venomous animal (6213)

metadata.title: Gored, rammed by animal
metadata.definition: Contact with a charging or butting animal with or without puncture by a horn.
metadata.includes: Rammed by goat
metadata.excludes: charged by rhino

metadata.title: Stepped on, kicked, trampled by animal
metadata.includes: Stepped on by a horse
metadata.excludes: knocked down and run over by running goats

metadata.title: Mauled, clawed, scratched by animal
metadata.includes: Clawed or scratched by cat

metadata.title: Struck by animal— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Contact with animal that does not fit descriptions of codes 6220-6223
metadata.includes: Struck by flying animal such as birds and bats
metadata.excludes: spit on

metadata.title: Multiple types of contact with animals
metadata.definition: Combination of one of more contact codes from 620 to 6229.
metadata.includes: Scratched and bitten by a cat
metadata.excludes: Insects bites (6211)

metadata.title: Contact with animals— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Contact with animals when a more specific event code that is known but does not fit descriptions of event codes from 621 to 628.
metadata.includes: Contact with poisonous or allergenic animal, such as jelly fish; spit on; sat on; animal falling on person; animal throws feces; contact with quills or barbs

metadata.title: Collapse, engulfment
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to incidents that are the result of a being struck by a collapsing structure or equipment or an engulfment in material.
metadata.includes: Compression, crushing, depletion of oxygen or drowning from cave-in or collapse; struck by falling debris during cave-in or collapse
metadata.excludes: Collapse caused by fire or explosion (Division 3)

metadata.title: Collapse, engulfment— unspecified
metadata.definition: Collapse of or engulfment in structures or material when a more specific event code from 6310 to 6390 cannot be determined.
metadata.excludes: Falls resulting from structure or equipment collapse (Division 4)

metadata.title: Collapse, engulfment— closed mine or tunnel
metadata.definition: Collapse of closed tunnel or mine
metadata.includes: Partial collapse of mine wall or roof
metadata.excludes: cave-in

metadata.title: Collapse, engulfment— open trench or excavation
metadata.definition: Collapse or cave-in of any man-made cut, cavity, trench, or depression in the earth’s surface formed by earth removal
metadata.includes: Trench wall collapse or cave-in
metadata.excludes: removed earth falling back into the excavation

metadata.title: Collapse, engulfment— loose materials or liquids
metadata.definition: Partial or total engulfment in loose materials or liquids. May involve sinking into materials or being overtaken by collapsing or surging materials
metadata.includes: Collapsing grain; sinking in loose materials; quicksand; manure pits; collapse or surge of materials due to natural disasters including tsunami, tidal wave, flood waters, rockslide, mudslide, avalanche
metadata.excludes: Falls into liquids or loose materials (Division 4)

metadata.title: Collapse, engulfment— building or structure
metadata.definition: Struck by or buried in materials breaking loose from buildings and structures in the process of full or partial collapse. Person may be in or on collapsing structure or outside within striking distance of materials.
metadata.includes: Whole building collapse
metadata.excludes: struck by debris from ceiling collapse

metadata.title: Collapse, engulfment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Collapse or engulfment event that is known but does not fit descriptions of event codes 631 to 634
metadata.includes: palm frond collapse
metadata.excludes: struck by collapsing boom (except permanent and semi-permanent tower cranes)

metadata.title: Struck by propelled, falling, or suspended object
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries that are the result of being struck by a propelled object or substance; self-propelled flying object; or falling, discharged, dislodged or detached objects.
metadata.includes: Thrown ball or other object; self-propelled flying object; discarded, dislodged or detached objects; free falling objects; objects dropped by a person; objects falling from running equipment
metadata.excludes: Intentional violent acts (Division 1)

metadata.title: Struck by propelled, falling, or suspended object— unspecified
metadata.definition: Struck by a propelled object or substance self-propelled flying object or falling, discharged, dislodged or detached objects when a more specific event code from 641 to 6429 cannot be determined.
metadata.excludes: Intentional violent acts (Division 1)

metadata.title: Gun discharge— accidental or intent unknown
metadata.definition: Shot by firearm due to accidental discharge or when fired in a nonviolent situation. The shooter can be either the injured worker or another person.
metadata.includes: Gun discharged while cleaning; accidently shot during hunting trip; accidental harm from shooting during training exercise, sport
metadata.excludes: Intentional violent acts (Division 1)

metadata.title: Struck by propelled object or substance
metadata.definition: Struck by objects or substances that have been thrown, hurled, or propelled across space.
metadata.includes: Thrown ball or other object; self-propelled flying object; discarded, dislodged or detached objects; discharged or flying objects
metadata.excludes: Intentional violent acts (Division 1)

metadata.title: Struck by propelled object or substance— unspecified
metadata.definition: Struck by objects or substances that have been thrown, hurled, or propelled across space when a more specific code from 6421 to 6429 cannot be determined.
