metadata.excludes: struck by debris from explosions (31)

metadata.title: Struck by discharged object or substance
metadata.definition: Struck by object(s) that are sprayed or discharged under power or pressure, usually by a tool or equipment designed for that purpose.
metadata.includes: Air compressor blasts, power washer blasts, fire hose, nail gun
metadata.excludes: Struck by a flying piece or particle that has broken off an object (6422)

metadata.title: Struck by dislodged or detached object(s)
metadata.definition: Struck by dislodged flying object or particle when a piece of material separates from or breaks off of a tool, machine, or other object that is not intended to separate.
metadata.includes: Flying broken glass or other particles; a piece of grinding wheel flying off; tire rims flying off (unless the tire or rim exploded); piece of material separating from a tool; rope, chain or fastener snapping
metadata.excludes: Air compressor blasts, power washer blasts, fire hose, nail gun, accidentally discharged by another person (6421); accidentally discharged gun (BB, stun, paintball) (641); items kicked back by machinery without being thrown or becoming detached, saw kickback (651); explosions (31)

metadata.title: Struck by other propelled object or substance— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Struck by an object being propelled across space that is known but does not fit descriptions of event codes  6421 to 6422.
metadata.includes: Thrown object
metadata.excludes: object propelled by wind

metadata.title: Struck by falling object
metadata.definition: Struck by objects and equipment slipping or falling freely by force of gravity.
metadata.includes: Objects and equipment tipping over, dropped by a person or falling from running equipment such as a conveyor; unattached items that are slipping or sliding off of a surface
metadata.excludes: Struck by falling doors, still attached (e.g. garage doors) (6441)

metadata.title: Struck by falling object— unspecified
metadata.definition: Struck by objects falling freely downward by force of gravity where a more specific code from 6431 to 6439 cannot be determined.
metadata.excludes: Objects being propelled by a force other than gravity (642)

metadata.title: Struck by object dropped by person
metadata.definition: Struck by object of any size dropped by or falling from the injured worker or by another person
metadata.includes: Dropped item on foot
metadata.excludes: items dropped from roof onto workers below

metadata.title: Struck by object tipping over
metadata.definition: Struck by any object or equipment that is self supporting on the ground surface tipping over but not moving under power and not the result of a collapse.
metadata.includes: Outrigger failure, shelf or file cabinet tipping over
metadata.excludes: Collapsing structures or equipment (634); boom collapse (634); struck by objects as a result of transportation incidents (Division2), fires or explosions (Division 3)

metadata.title: Struck by falling part of vehicle or machine, still attached
metadata.definition: Struck by attached parts of vehicles or equipment that fall or descend in an uncontrolled fashion.
metadata.includes: Falling dump bed
metadata.excludes: falling forks (forklifts)

metadata.title: Struck by other falling object— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Struck by a falling object event that is known but does not fit descriptions of event codes 6431 to 6433. The object is free falling and not dropped by a person, not falling from running equipment and not a tipping over.
metadata.includes: Falling tree or tree branch
metadata.excludes: vehicle falling from stationary jacks

metadata.title: Struck by suspended or swinging object
metadata.definition: Events where the worker was struck by objects and equipment parts that are suspended or swinging from a fixed point. It excludes handheld objects. The item(s) may be suspended from powered equipment or non-powered fixed points.

metadata.title: Struck by suspended or swinging objects— unspecified
Struck by door, gate, window
metadata.definition: Powered or nonpowered doors, gates, or windows that may be raising, lowering or swinging from hinges
metadata.includes: Hand and caught in vehicle door, struck by lowering garage door, caught in revolving door, hand caught in powered or nonpowered window
metadata.excludes: Falling vehicle tailgate (6433)

metadata.title: Struck by suspended or swinging objects— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Struck by parts or objects that are suspended or swinging from an object or equipment
metadata.includes: Struck by crane block or load
metadata.excludes: items suspended on nonpowered track (gantry crane)

metadata.title: Struck by propelled, falling, or suspended object— n.e.c.
Struck, caught, or compressed by running powered equipment
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries that are the result of the motion all types of equipment and machinery running under power, except discharged, falling, or suspended and swinging objects. Incidents are assumed to occur during normal operation unless case documents indicate otherwise. The detailed codes describe what kind of machine motion produced the harmful contact between worker and machine.
metadata.includes: Contact with running machinery and equipment including industrial machinery, mobile equipment (except during transport); running, powered hand-wielded equipment; includes running water or water hoses (assume powered by pump)

metadata.title: Struck by running powered equipment— unspecified
metadata.definition: Contact with all types of equipment and machinery running under power, when a more specific code from 651 to 659 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: Contact with running machinery and equipment including industrial machinery and mobile equipment (except during transport); running, powered hand-wielded equipment
metadata.excludes: Struck by running equipment being pushed by person (6622) or moving across a surface under power (unless contact was with moving machine parts) (653)

metadata.title: Struck by running powered equipment— irregular movement, kick back
metadata.definition: Contact or jarring resulting from machinery or materials being processed by machinery striking the worker due to recoil or sudden backward motion.
metadata.includes: Saw kickback
metadata.excludes: kick back of wood being cut

metadata.title: Struck by running powered equipment— during maintenance, cleaning, testing
metadata.definition: Contact with powered equipment during non-normal operation. This may include unplanned repairs and interventions, such as troubleshooting or unjamming as well as planned cleaning and maintenance.
metadata.includes: Contact while cleaning, lubricating, unjamming, repairing, calibrating, testing, performing maintenance
metadata.excludes: Contact while loading, unloading (662)

metadata.title: Caught, entangled in running powered equipment— normal operation
metadata.definition: Contact with running machinery and equipment when a person, clothing, or part of body is pulled into moving parts of machinery or equipment.
metadata.includes: Clothing caught in running machinery and equipment in non-normal operation
metadata.excludes: chipper incidents in non-normal operation

metadata.title: Compressed between running equipment and other object(s)
metadata.definition: Struck or compressed between moving part of machine and another object or structure.
metadata.includes: Compressed between manlift platform and ceiling; compressed between machine arm and other object; pinned against wall by machine; caught in mechanical doors, gates, and windows
metadata.excludes: Pinned between vehicle body and attached vehicle part (665)

metadata.title: Struck by rolling powered vehicle or machinery
metadata.definition: Struck by a machine or vehicle moving over the ground surface that does not meet the definition of a transportation incident. That is, the machine is either not performing transportation functions (i.e. moving goods or persons) or is not in normal operation (i.e. moving outside of the control of a person or computer)
metadata.includes: Struck by moving machinery not involved in transport (e.g. robotic vacuum cleaner or inventory checker)
metadata.excludes: struck by runaway vehicle (non-normal operation)

metadata.title: Jarred, vibrated by running powered equipment
metadata.definition: Cumulative trauma and injuries resulting from repeated or prolonged exposure to vibration or jarring.
metadata.includes: Riding in jarring vehicle, without a specific transportation incident; acute injuries due to jarring and vibration of running machinery or nonpowered tools and objects
metadata.excludes: vibration or jarring due to a transportation incident (2); abrasion due to short contact with powered equipment, such as belt sander (639)

metadata.title: Struck by running powered equipment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Struck by attached parts of running machinery and equipment.  Machine parts may be swinging, rotating, rising or lowering.
metadata.includes: Pushed by machine parts into another object, such as lifts compressing worker between lift platform and another object or surface; striking against part of powered equipment in operation
metadata.excludes: Struck by object or machine part detached from equipment (6422)

metadata.title: Contact with non-running objects or equipment
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries that are the result of striking against or being struck by an object that is neither collapsing, falling, or propelled or operating under power. This group includes objects manipulated or wielded by the injured worker. Items or equipment being moved or wielded by other persons
metadata.includes: Walked into a wall, entangled in wire
metadata.excludes: Contact with running equipment and objects in normal or non-normal operation (65); falling objects or equipment (643); propelled, dislodged or discharged objects or substances (642); transportation incidents (Division 2)

metadata.title: Contact with non-running objects or equipment— unspecified
metadata.definition: Striking against or being struck by a non-running object that is not falling, moving over a surface or has not been discharged, dislodged or propelled when a more specific event code from 661 to 669 cannot be determined.
metadata.excludes: Vehicles and powered mobile equipment (non-transportation) (65)

metadata.title: Injured by object handled by person
metadata.definition: Accidental contact resulting from a worker being struck by an object or equipment being handled or manipulated in some way by direct physical exertion of a person, either the injured worker themselves or another person.
metadata.excludes: Powered tools or equipment whose operation does not involve direct physical exertion of a person (i.e. mechanically operated or remote-controlled machinery) (65)

metadata.title: Injured by object handled by person— unspecified
Injured by object held or wielded by person
metadata.definition: Accidental contact resulting from a worker being struck by an object or equipment being wielded or handled by themselves or another person
metadata.includes: Object breaking in hand
metadata.excludes: injured by handheld object

metadata.title: Injured by object pushed or pulled by person
metadata.definition: Accidental contact resulting from a worker being struck by an object or equipment being pushed or pulled by another person
metadata.includes: Turning, steering object not supported by injured worker

metadata.title: Injured by object handled by person— n.e.c.
metadata.excludes: Overexertion injuries (Division 7)

metadata.title: Entangled in non-running object
metadata.definition: Objects that become wrapped around worker or part of body.
metadata.includes: Wrapped or surrounded by wire, rope, plastic
metadata.excludes: Caught or struck in collapsing structure (63)

metadata.title: Struck by rolling, sliding, or shifting objects—non-running
metadata.definition: Struck by rolling, sliding or shifting objects and equipment, except self-propelled, running powered equipment; items being pushed or pulled by person(s) or objects being advanced or propelled by powered equipment
metadata.includes: Rolling shopping cart, non running powered pallet jack sliding across a surface; struck by rolling logs or pipes; struck by object or equipment moving along fixed track (except transportation); struck by shifting stone slabs
metadata.excludes: Self-propelled, running powered equipment (653); items being pushed or pulled by person(s) (6622);  objects being advanced or propelled by powered equipment (659)

metadata.title: Caught or wedged between objects— nonrunning
metadata.definition: Impeded, caught, compressed or pinched in the parts of a single object or non-running equipment or between two objects or non-running equipment.
metadata.includes: Caught hand between objects
metadata.excludes: positional asphyxia

metadata.title: Struck against stationary object
metadata.definition: Codes in this group apply to injuries resulting from a person striking against an object where the impact is caused by the bodily motion of the injured person.
metadata.excludes: intentionally striking or punching an object in anger or outburst (129)

metadata.title: Struck against stationary object— unspecified
metadata.definition: Injuries resulting from a person striking against an object where the impact is caused by the bodily motion of the injured person and a more detailed code from 6651 to 6659 cannot be determined

metadata.title: Stepped or knelt on object
metadata.definition: Making impact with an object by stepping on it, where the injury is from the impact not a loss of balance.
metadata.includes: Stepping on nail
metadata.excludes: kneeling on object

metadata.title: Walked or ran into stationary object
metadata.definition: Injuries from inadvertently walking into an object or structure.
metadata.includes: Worker runs into wall
metadata.excludes: Trips without falls (42, 432)

metadata.title: Struck against stationary object while rising, lowering
metadata.definition: Injuries resulting from a person striking against an object where the impact is caused by the bodily motion of the injured person rising up from a crouched or seated position
metadata.includes: Strike head while crawling, crouching under something

metadata.title: Struck against stationary object— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Injuries resulting from a person striking against an object where the impact is caused by the bodily motion of the injured person that do not meet descriptions of 6651 through 6653
metadata.includes: Splinters from non-handheld objects (e.g. railing); jarring injuries from repeated striking of non-powered tools, such as a hammer or axe
metadata.excludes: Contact with moving or running parts (65)

metadata.title: Rubbed or abraded by non-running object
metadata.definition: Injuries or discomfort resulting from acute or prolonged exposure to friction or pressure.
metadata.includes: Blisters and chafing from worn apparel
metadata.excludes: blister from wielding tools

metadata.title: Other contact with non-running objects or equipment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Contact with non-running objects or equipment that is known but does not fit descriptions of event codes 661 or 666.
metadata.includes: zip line incidents
metadata.excludes: jarred or jerked by non-powered object

metadata.title: Contact— n.e.c.
OVEREXERTION, REPETITIVE MOTION, AND BODILY CONDITIONS
metadata.definition: Codes in this division apply to injuries that are the result of either excessive physical effort over an outside source, free bodily motion, the assumption of an unnatural position, repetition of a bodily motion, maintaining one position for an extended period, or a combination of any of these.
metadata.includes: Heart attacks and strokes not attributed to a specific event or exposure; "Ergonomic injuries"
metadata.excludes: Overexertion injuries occurring onboard vehicles in transport (Division 2); abnormal stepping, loss of balance, trips, slips or falls and injuries from attempting to recover from these events (Division 4)

metadata.title: Overexertion, repetitive motion and bodily condition— unspecified
metadata.definition: Overexertion or ergonomic Injury not stated to be caused by violence, transportation, fire or explosion, fall, exposure, or contact, and a more specific code from 710 through 799 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: Overexertion or ergonomic injury from normal or regular duties; working at work station; strain due to installation; scrubbing, cleaning, dusting, etc. without additional information

metadata.title: Overexertion while moving or manipulating external object(s)
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries that are the result of excessive physical effort directed at an outside source, either as a single or cumulative exposure.
metadata.includes: Lifting/lowering, pulling/pushing/turning, moving/transferring, holding/carrying/wielding, or catching/throwing an object or person
metadata.excludes: Non-overexertion injuries from contact with a person (61)

metadata.title: Overexertion while moving or manipulating external object(s)— unspecified
metadata.definition: Overexertions involving an outside source for an unspecified length of time and unspecified number of repetitions when the type of exertion reflected in codes 711 through 719 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: "Moving" an object without further information; unspecified overexertion involving an object or person such as cleaning or making a bed
metadata.excludes: Moving a patient (711)

metadata.title: Overexertion while providing medical or custodial care
metadata.definition: Overexertion incurred while attempting to move or physically assist a person when the worker bears part or all of another person's weight or exerts against another person's strength.
metadata.includes: Transferring, repositioning, or turning  a patient; overexertion from assisting or helping a patient/person without further information; catching a falling patient or child; Pushing or pulling a patient in a wheelchair, bed, or stretcher
metadata.excludes: overexertion when restraining a violent person (Division 1); veterinary care (711); pushing or pulling a bed, wheelchair or stretcher without a patient or if it is unknown if there was a patient (714)

metadata.title: Overexertion while wielding, manipulating tools, object(s)
metadata.definition: Overexertions from combinations of gross motor movements and exertions while wielding handtools or manipulating other objects.
metadata.includes: Shoveling; cranking; hammering; single instance use of handheld tools/objects, such as shoveling;  interacting with levers or switches; turning a crank handle; manually jacking up a vehicle; turning or rotating objects without relocating them; opening doors or windows; tightening

metadata.title: Overexertion while catching or throwing object(s)
metadata.definition: Overexertion from throwing or catching an object or person, either once or repeatedly, when injury is not caused by impact with the thrown object.
metadata.includes: Repetitive throwing of boxes
metadata.excludes: heaving or swinging heavy objects

metadata.title: Overexertion while materials moving by hand
metadata.definition: Overexertions from bearing the weight of or striving against the resistance of an object while trying to relocate or position it. The overexertion may be a single episode or the result of prolonged or multiple instances of exertion. This includes lifting, lowering, pushing, pulling, turning, and other manners of exertion.
metadata.includes: Lifting, lowering, carrying, supporting, handling, holding, or placing an object;  stocking merchandise; team lifting large objects; pushing, pulling or turning objects or equipment over ground surface, with or without wheels; moving objects up or down stairs; moving furniture; unloading freight; Pushing or pulling a wheelchair, bed, or stretcher that was empty or if it was unknown whether there was a patient.

metadata.title: Multiple types of overexertion while moving or manipulating external object(s)
metadata.definition: Combination of overexertions from at least 2 different codes 711 through 714, occurring either once or multiple times.
metadata.includes: Overexertion catching a dropped object and then moving it
metadata.excludes: Pushing cart and unloading cart

metadata.title: Overexertion while moving or manipulating external object(s)— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Overexertion for which the event is known but does not fit descriptions of event codes 710 to 718.
metadata.includes: Kicking a ball; attempting to stop a rolling object; overexertion or ergonomic injury from worn apparel or items (e.g. backpacks, utility belts); overexertion while working with animals, animal husbandry, veterinary care
metadata.excludes: Bearing down on shovel with foot (712)

metadata.title: Repetitive microtasks
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply injuries or conditions resulting from motions (often micro tasks) that impose stress or strain on some part of the body due to the repetitive nature of the task.
metadata.includes: Repetitive micro tasks
metadata.excludes: Strenuous effort or exertion imposed against an outside source (71); repetitive (cumulative trauma), vibration

metadata.title: Repetitive microtasks— unspecified
metadata.definition: Repetitive motion without overexertion that does not have enough information to choose a more specific event code from 721 through 729.
metadata.includes: Repetitive motion
metadata.excludes: clerical activities

metadata.title: Repetitive microtasks involving computers, electronics
metadata.definition: Repetitive motion involving data entry tools or equipment
metadata.includes: Repeated use of computer peripherals, cash registers, or cellular phones; gaming equipment; touch screens

metadata.title: Repetitive use of tools, instruments
metadata.definition: Repetitive motion involving the use of simple tools or equipment without overexertion.
metadata.includes: Repeated use of screwdrivers, knives, musical instruments, or surgical implements; musical instruments; product assembly
metadata.excludes: Holding or wielding a heavy tool (712)

metadata.title: Multiple types of repetitive microtasks
metadata.definition: Combination of at least 2 different repetitive motions from codes 721 through 722.
metadata.includes: Trigger finger caused by a combination of texting and using handheld tools

metadata.title: Repetitive microtasks— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Specific repetitive motion, not involving tools and/or instruments that is known but does not fit the description of event codes from 721 through 728.
metadata.includes: Sign language interpretation, scanning groceries, assembly-line work without tools; stepping on pedal repeatedly; voice strain after prolonged talking/shouting
metadata.excludes: Moving heavy objects (714)

metadata.title: Bodily position and motion
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group apply to injuries or conditions resulting from a single or prolonged instance(s) of free bodily motion or the assumption of a physical position without other incident, which impose stress or strain upon some part of the body.
metadata.includes: prolonged sitting, standing, or viewing; musculoskeletal or other injury or illnesses resulting from the execution of personal movements such as walking, climbing, or bending when such movement in itself was the source of injury or illness; eyestrain from sustained viewing (737)
metadata.excludes: overexertion from lifting, pulling, or pushing outside objects  (71); motions involving microtasks which induce injury or illness due to their repetitive nature (72); abnormal stepping, loss of balance, trips, slips and falls, which are coded in (4); injuries from attempting to catch oneself while falling or recover balance after slipping or tripping (4)

metadata.title: Bodily position and motion— unspecified
metadata.definition: Bodily motion, either a single episode or prolonged, when the specific action is unknown and a more specific event code from 731 through 739 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: Body parts "giving out" with no explanation or external source
metadata.excludes: Repetitive dexterous tasks (72)

metadata.title: Climbing or stepping— up or down
metadata.definition: Overexertion from raising or lowering self from one surface to another without stumble, loss or balance or other incident. This can be a single episode or prolonged.
metadata.includes: Strained back when ascending or descending stairs, ladders, or inclines; overexertion while boarding and alighting vehicles; "hoisting" oneself to a higher level or surface
metadata.excludes: Stepping on a flat surface (736); slip, trip, stumble while stepping, loss of balance, fall (43); "missed step" (42); twisting ankle due to stepping on uneven surface (432)

metadata.title: Kneeling, crawling
metadata.definition: Bodily movement involving a single or prolonged episode of body weight being placed on knees through kneeling or crawling. It also includes assuming a kneeling position and changing from a kneeling position to another position.
metadata.includes: The process of kneeling down
metadata.excludes: being in kneeling position

metadata.title: Twisting, reaching, bending
metadata.definition: Bodily movement involving a single or prolonged episode of twisting, extending, or contorting oneself in attempts to reach items or fit into spaces.
metadata.includes: Straining for out of reach items
metadata.excludes: squeezing through tight spaces

metadata.title: Standing up, sitting down, laying down
metadata.definition: Bodily movement involving a single or prolonged episode of sustained stance or position or repeated transition between standing, sitting or laying.
metadata.includes: Laying down under a vehicle to perform repair work
metadata.excludes: standing from a seated position

metadata.title: Running, without other incident
metadata.definition: Running without loss of balance, abnormal step, or stepping on an object or uneven surface.
metadata.includes: Single episode of running to pursue suspect
metadata.excludes: running during athletic training or competition

metadata.title: Walking, without other incident
metadata.definition: Walking without loss of balance, abnormal step, or stepping on an object or uneven surface.
metadata.includes: knee "popped" while walking
metadata.excludes: walking up steps (731)

metadata.title: Sustained bodily position
metadata.definition: Holding a natural position for any length of time that does not fit the description of event codes 731 through 734.
metadata.includes: Poor workstation ergonomics, including seats on vehicles in transport in the absence of a transportation incident; prolonged or brief episodes of sitting, standing or squatting; sustained viewing of screens or monitors; operating a vehicle without transportation incident or rough driving surface
metadata.excludes: Welder's flash, staring at the sun (522)

metadata.title: Multiple types of bodily position and motion
metadata.definition: Combination of at least two bodily reactions from codes 731 through 737 without loss of balance, abnormal step, or stepping on an object.
metadata.includes: Single or repeated episodes of standing and walking, walking and running, or kneeling and standing,

metadata.title: Bodily position and motion—  n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Bodily motion that is known but does not fit the description of event codes from 731 through 738.
metadata.includes: Jumping up and down
metadata.excludes: push-ups or pull-ups

metadata.title: Bodily conditions
metadata.definition: Injuries or illnesses that are the direct result of the physical condition of the worker with no outside injury component.
metadata.includes: Heart attacks and strokes which are not attributed to a specific event or exposure; unexplained fainting; vertigo, motion sickness if not related to transportation
metadata.excludes: Bodily conditions exacerbated by workplace events or exposures (code to appropriate event); anxiety or other mental symptoms or disorders due to violent incidents (11), witnessing a violent act (13), transportation incidents (Division 2) or stressful environments (57)

metadata.title: Multiple types of overexertions, bodily motion and position
metadata.definition: Combination of at least two separate, sequential events from the overexertion involving external objects (71), repetitive microtasks (72), bodily position and motion (73) and bodily conditions (74) during a single or prolonged episode.
metadata.includes: Assembly line work involving exertion of strength and repetitive microtasks
metadata.excludes: Lifting materials and turning (714)

metadata.title: Event or exposure— unspecified
metadata.definition: Select this code when there is not enough information present to select a code from any of the major event divisions (1-7).
